iamiherald.com/1060/story/549245.html \n |archivedate=May 28, 2008 \n}}\n\n</ref>\nThomas, and three of his brothers, are graduates of the [[United States Naval Academy]]. All are retired, including one who was in the Marine Corps. Another brother served in the Peace Corps. His two uncles also were Navy officers via Officers' Candidate School programs. \nThomas graduated in 1981.\n\nThomas was a 1976 graduate of [[Thomas Sprigg Wootton High School]] in Rockville, Maryland.\n\n==Navy career==\nIn 1999, Thomas commanded the [[destroyer]] [[USS Ross (DDG-71)|USS ''Ross'']].<ref name=MiamiHeraldAboutThomas20080528/>  \nHe has served aboard the [[USS Shreveport (LPD-12)|USS ''Shreveport'']], [[USS Estocin (FFG-15)|USS ''Estocin'']], [[USS Willamette (AO-180)|USS ''Willamette'']], and the [[USS Leyte Gulf (CG-55)|USS ''Leyte Gulf'']]\n\n==9-11 rescue efforts==\n[[File:David Thomas -- smithsonian uniform.jpg|thumb|The fire-damaged uniform Thomas was wearing on 9-11.]]\n\nCaptain David Thomas was serving in [[the Pentagon]] on [[September 11, 2001]], when [[al Qaeda]] [[Aircraft hijacking|hijackers]] crashed a passenger jet into it, causing an explosion, fire, and consequent injuries and loss of life.<ref name=MiamiHerald20080528/>\nThomas was one of the people who spontaneously volunteered to enter the damaged part of the building to rescue survivors.\n\nWhen asked about his rescue efforts on September 11, Thomas replied:\n\n{{quote|I am who I am, a trained sailor who sails ships at sea. You run toward your shipmate in times of trouble.}}\n\nHis fire-damaged uniform now hangs in the [[Smithsonian]]'s American History gallery.<ref name=MiamiHerald20080528/>\n\n==8th Commander of Joint Task Force Guantanamo==\n[[File:Mark Buzby hands over Guantanamo to David Thomas.jpg|thumb|[[Mark Buzby]] hands over [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo]] to David M. Thomas.]]\nOn May 27, 2008, [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] David Thomas replaced Rear Admiral [[Mark Buzby]] to become the 8th Commander of [[Joint Task Force Guantanamo]], and the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]].<ref name=MiamiHerald20080528/>\n\nOn April 2, 2009, Thomas defended inviting visiting VIP entertainers to view detainees at Guantanamo.<ref name=MiamiHerald2009-04-02>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.miamiherald.com/1218/story/981305.html\n |title       = Prison camps commander defends celebrity visits\n |publisher   = [[Miami Herald]]\n |author      = Carol Rosenberg\n |date        = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.miamiherald.com%2F1218%2Fstory%2F981305.html&date=2009-04-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n[[Miss Universe 2008]] [[Dayana Mendoza]] and \n[[Miss USA 2008]] [[Crystle Stewart]] had both been invited to visit Guantanamo on a [[USO]] tour, where they signed autographs.  Both women stirred controversy after they published accounts of their visits.  Thomas had authorized the women to view captives.<ref name=NYTimes2009-03-30>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/30/miss-universe-visits-guantanamo/?hp\n |title       = Miss Universe Visits Guant\u00e1namo Bay\n |work=[[The New York Times]]\n |date        = 2009-03-30\n |author      = Robert Mackey\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fthelede.blogs.nytimes.com%2F2009%2F03%2F30%2Fmiss-universe-visits-guantanamo%2F%3Fhp&date=2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes2009-04-01>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/04/01/miss-universes-blog-adds-to-guantanamo-debate/\n |title       = Miss Universe's Blog Post on Guant\u00e1namo Vanishes\n |work=The New York Times\n |date        = 2009-04-01\n |author      = Robert Mackey\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fthelede.blogs.nytimes.com%2F2009%2F04%2F01%2Fmiss-universes-blog-adds-to-guantanamo-debate%2F&date=2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=TheTimes2009-04-01>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/hugo_rifkind/article6024665.ece\n |title       = Life is lovely when you're wearing a tiara\n |publisher   = [[The Times]]\n |author      = Hugo Rifkind\n |date        = 2009-04-03\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.timesonline.co.uk%2Ftol%2Fcomment%2Fcolumnists%2Fhugo_rifkind%2Farticle6024665.ece&date=2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |location    = London\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost2009-04-02>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/31/AR2009033103729.html?hpid=news-col-blog\n |title       = 'GWOT.' What Is It Good For? Absolutely Nothing!\n |publisher   = [[The Washington Post]]\n |author      = Al Kamen\n |date        = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fwp-dyn%2Fcontent%2Farticle%2F2009%2F03%2F31%2FAR2009033103729.html%3Fhpid%3Dnews-col-blog&date=2009-04-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=Independent2009-04-01>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/ian-odoherty/bloody-wimmin-ruining-history-1694971.html\n |title       = Bloody Wimmin, ruining history\n |author      = Ian O'Doherty\n |publisher   = [[The Independent (Ireland)]]\n |date        = 2009-04-02\n |accessdate  = 2009-04-02\n |archivedate = 2009-04-02\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.independent.ie%2Fopinion%2Fcolumnists%2Fian-odoherty%2Fbloody-wimmin-ruining-history-1694971.html&date=2009-04-02\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n[[Carol Rosenberg]], reporting in the ''[[Miami Herald]]'', wrote that Thomas \"brushed aside\" concerns that by allowing civilians to view the captives he was violating the clause in the Geneva Conventions that protect captives from the humiliation of public display.\n\nThomas asserted that the beauty queens had been allowed to view the detainees in Guantanamo just as if they were reporters.<ref name=MiamiHerald2009-04-02/>\n\n==Commander, Naval Surface Forces Atlantic==\n\nOn July 10, 2009, he began his assignment as commander, [[Carrier Strike Group Two|Carrier Strike Group 2]], serving in that capacity until July, 2010.  In July 2010, he was named Commander, Naval Surface Forces Atlantic (COMNAVSURFLANT), the senior Surface Warfare Officer (SWO) in the Atlantic Fleet, a position he held until September 4, 2013.<ref name=militarynews2013-09-04/>\n\n==BAE==\n\nAfter he left the Navy Thomas was hired as an executive at [[BAE]], a firm which builds and maintains large vessels, including [[US Navy]] vessels.<ref name=marinelink2018-02-09/>  In 2018 he was put in charge of BAE's [[San Diego, California|San Diego]] facilty.<ref name=sdbj2018-09-09/>\n\n==References==\n<!-- \n| archivedate = | url-status = live | archiveurl =  \n| url-status = live | archivedate = | archiveurl =  \n| url-status = dead | archivedate = | archiveurl =  \n -->\n{{Reflist|refs= \n<ref name=sdbj2018-09-09>\n{{cite news\n| url         = https://www.sdbj.com/news/2018/sep/09/ship-shape/\n| title       = New Leader, Bigger Dry Dock Working at Shipyard\n| work        = [[San Diego Business Journal]]\n| author      = Brad Graves\n| date        = 2018-09-09\n| location    = [[San Diego, California]]\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20180910034746/http://sdbj.com/news/2018/sep/09/ship-shape/\n| archivedate = 2018-09-10\n| accessdate  = 2020-01-16\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = Eight months into his new assignment, Thomas said he isn\u2019t planning any changes in San Diego. However, there is evidence the yard will be dealing with a greater volume of work than it did under Thomas\u2019 predecessor.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=militarynews2013-09-04>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/news/top_stories/naval-surface-force-atlantic-holds-change-of-command/article_af680702-c614-5b46-a0b5-266309127475.html\n| title       = Naval Surface Force Atlantic holds change of command\n| work        = [[Military News]]\n| date        = 2013-09-04\n| location    = [[Norfolk, Virginia]]\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200118041404/https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/news/top_stories/naval-surface-force-atlantic-holds-change-of-command/article_af680702-c614-5b46-a0b5-266309127475.html\n| archivedate = 2020-01-18\n| accessdate  = 2020-01-16\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = Rear Adm. Pete A. Gumataotao relieved Rear. Adm. David M. Thomas, Jr. as Commander, Naval Surface Force Atlantic (SURFLANT) during a ceremony at the Naval Support Activity Norfolk chapel, Aug. 29. \n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=marinelink2018-02-09>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.marinelink.com/news/jacksonville-destination433819\n| title       = BAE Systems Jacksonville: Ship Repair's 'Destination of Choice'\n| work        = [[Marine Link]]\n| author      = Greg Trauthwein\n| date        = 2018-02-09\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200118041101/https://www.marinelink.com/news/jacksonville-destination433819\n| archivedate = 2020-01-18\n| accessdate  = 2020-01-16\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = In fact, since Thomas took command of the yard in 2014 (*Note: David M. Thomas, Jr., was recently named to lead BAE ship repair yard in San Diego after three years as Vice President & General Manager, Southeast Shipyards, Ship Repair, BAE Systems in Jacksonville), he credits a change in people skills as one of the leading changes at the yard during his tenure.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|David M. Thomas}}\n*[http://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/navybio.asp?bioID=429 Official U.S. Navy Biography]\n* {{USNAVY|article=Rear Admiral David M. Thomas, Jr|url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/navybio.asp?bioID=429}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, David M.}}\n[[Category:Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_M._Thomas_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Nassima Saifi", "text_new": "{{short description|Algerian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Nassima Saifi\n| image =\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = Algerian\n| sport = Athletics (track)\n| country = Algeria\n| worlds = \n| event  =\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1988|10|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mila Province|Mila]], Algeria\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| disability      = Limb deficiency\n| disability_class = [[T58 (classification)|F58]]\n| club            = GSP Alger\n| coach           = Hocine Saadoune\n| height = {{convert|180|cm}}\n| weight = \n| pb =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{ALG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics - Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T56/57]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F56/F57]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]] | [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F58]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan Arab Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 Pan Arab Games|2011 Doha]] |[[Athletics at the 2011 Pan Arab Games|Discus throw - F57/58]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2011 Pan Arab Games|2011 Doha]] |[[Athletics at the 2011 Pan Arab Games|Shot put - F57/58]]}}\n|}}\n\n'''Nassima Saifi''' ({{IPAc-en|n|\u0251\u02d0|\u02c8|s|\u026a|m|\u0251\u02d0|_|s|a\u026a|f|i\u02d0}};{{fix|text=stress?}} born 29 October 1988) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Algeria]] competing mainly in category [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put F57\u201358|F58]] throwing events. Specialising in both the [[discus throw]] and [[shot put]], Saifi is a double Paralympic gold medal winner and three time [[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Champion]].\n\n==Personal history==\nSaifi was born in [[Mila Province|Mila]], Algeria in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_QA2015AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=2893.htm|title=Saifi, Nassima|work=Paralympic.org|accessdate=4 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923084220/https://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_QA2015AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=2893.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Born able-bodied, she had her left leg amputated following after being hit by a car in 1998.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=687351&refreshauto=1|title=Saifi, Nassima|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]|accessdate=4 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923084217/https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=687351&refreshauto=1|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Her father, realizing she needed something to work on in her spare time, encouraged her to take up an athletics career. She joined the Mila handisport club where she was able to train.<ref name=dj>{{cite web|url=http://www.djazairess.com/fr/horizons/179805|title=Nassima Saifi, championne du monde du lancer de disque|publisher=DjaZairess|accessdate=19 February 2017|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220020354/http://www.djazairess.com/fr/horizons/179805|archive-date=20 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Athletic career==\nThanks to her father's assistance and encouragement,<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> Saifi made her international debut for Algeria at the [[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Assen]]. She entered both the shot put and discus throw, finishing fifth in both.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> Saifi made her first appearance at a [[Summer Paralympics]] in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Games]] in [[Beijing]].<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> She entered both the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put F57\u201358|shot put]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw F57\u201358|discus throw]], finishing tenth and fourth respectively.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nSaifi's first major international success came at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, where she entered both the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|discus throw]] and the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put]]. Although finishing ninth in the shot, she threw a distance of 40.99 metres to win the gold medal, an  improvement of over six metres on her Beijing best.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/><ref name=\"dz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aps.dz/en/sports/14198-rio-paralympics-2016-discus-women-t57-gold-medal-for-algerian-nassima-saifi|title=Rio Paralympics 2016 (Discus-women/T57): Gold medal for Algerian Nassima Saifi|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=26 October 2016|work=aps.dz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027083024/http://www.aps.dz/en/sports/14198-rio-paralympics-2016-discus-women-t57-gold-medal-for-algerian-nassima-saifi|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The following year she appeared at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 Paralympics]] in London, winning gold in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics - Women's discus throw|discus]] and making her the joint World and Paralympic champion.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nAt the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 IPC World Championships]] in Lyon Saifi not only retained her discus title, but also won a bronze in the shot put, her first medal in the event at world level.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> The discus event was a close affair with Saifi requiring a world record throw of 42.05 metres to record a higher points tally over Ireland's [[Orla Barry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/athletics/2013/0727/464961-barry-claims-discus-silver-at-ipc-worlds/|title=Orla Barry claims discus silver at IPC World Athletics Championships|work=rte.ie|accessdate=26 October 2016|date=27 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027054829/http://www.rte.ie/sport/athletics/2013/0727/464961-barry-claims-discus-silver-at-ipc-worlds/|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years later in Doha, Saifi claimed her third consecutive World [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|discus]] title in her class.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nIn preparation for the Paralympics, she was trained by Hocine Saadoun for three hours a day, every day, except for weekends.<ref name=dz/>\nSaifi cemented her position as one of the greatest Paralympic competitors at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]] in Rio. Despite throwing well below her best (her winning throw being 33.33 metres) she was still able to take the gold medal, making her unbeaten at world and Paralympic level since 2011.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> She also took silver in her less favoured shot put, her first at a Paralympics.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=nassima-saifi|old_id=687351}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saifi, Nassima}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Algerian female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Algerian female shot putters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:People from Mila Province]]\n[[Category:African Games gold medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:African Games medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:African Games silver medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2015 African Games]]\n[[Category:World Para Athletics Championships winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Algerian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Nassima Saifi\n| image =\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = Algerian\n| sport = Athletics (track)\n| country = Algeria\n| worlds = \n| event  =\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1988|10|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mila Province|Mila]], Algeria\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| disability      = Limb deficiency\n| disability_class = [[T58 (classification)|F58]]\n| club            = GSP Alger\n| coach           = Hocine Saadoune\n| height = {{convert|180|cm}}\n| weight = \n| pb =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{ALG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics - Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T56/57]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F56/F57]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]] | [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57/58]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|Discus - T57]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F58]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan Arab Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2011 Pan Arab Games|2011 Doha]] |[[Athletics at the 2011 Pan Arab Games|Discus throw - F57/58]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2011 Pan Arab Games|2011 Doha]] |[[Athletics at the 2011 Pan Arab Games|Shot put - F57/58]]}}\n|}}\n\n'''Nassima Saifi''' ({{IPAc-en|n|\u0251\u02d0|\u02c8|s|\u026a|m|\u0251\u02d0|_|s|a\u026a|f|i\u02d0}};{{fix|text=stress?}} born 29 October 1988) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Algeria]] competing mainly in category [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put F57\u201358|F58]] throwing events. Specialising in both the [[discus throw]] and [[shot put]], Saifi is a double Paralympic gold medal winner and three time [[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Champion]].\n\n==Personal history==\nSaifi was born in [[Mila Province|Mila]], Algeria in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_QA2015AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=2893.htm|title=Saifi, Nassima|work=Paralympic.org|accessdate=4 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923084220/https://www.paralympic.org/static/info/doha-2015/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_QA2015AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=2893.htm|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Born able-bodied, she had her left leg amputated following after being hit by a car in 1998.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=687351&refreshauto=1|title=Saifi, Nassima|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]|accessdate=4 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923084217/https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=687351&refreshauto=1|archive-date=23 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Her father, realizing she needed something to work on in her spare time, encouraged her to take up an athletics career. She joined the Mila handisport club where she was able to train.<ref name=dj>{{cite web|url=http://www.djazairess.com/fr/horizons/179805|title=Nassima Saifi, championne du monde du lancer de disque|publisher=DjaZairess|accessdate=19 February 2017|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220020354/http://www.djazairess.com/fr/horizons/179805|archive-date=20 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Athletic career==\nThanks to her father's assistance and encouragement,<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> Saifi made her international debut for Algeria at the [[2006 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Assen]]. She entered both the shot put and discus throw, finishing fifth in both.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> Saifi made her first appearance at a [[Summer Paralympics]] in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Games]] in [[Beijing]].<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> She entered both the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put F57\u201358|shot put]] and [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's discus throw F57\u201358|discus throw]], finishing tenth and fourth respectively.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nSaifi's first major international success came at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, where she entered both the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|discus throw]] and the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put]]. Although finishing ninth in the shot, she threw a distance of 40.99 metres to win the gold medal, an  improvement of over six metres on her Beijing best.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/><ref name=\"dz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aps.dz/en/sports/14198-rio-paralympics-2016-discus-women-t57-gold-medal-for-algerian-nassima-saifi|title=Rio Paralympics 2016 (Discus-women/T57): Gold medal for Algerian Nassima Saifi|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=26 October 2016|work=aps.dz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027083024/http://www.aps.dz/en/sports/14198-rio-paralympics-2016-discus-women-t57-gold-medal-for-algerian-nassima-saifi|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The following year she appeared at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 Paralympics]] in London, winning gold in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics - Women's discus throw|discus]] and making her the joint World and Paralympic champion.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nAt the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 IPC World Championships]] in Lyon Saifi not only retained her discus title, but also won a bronze in the shot put, her first medal in the event at world level.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> The discus event was a close affair with Saifi requiring a world record throw of 42.05 metres to record a higher points tally over Ireland's [[Orla Barry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/athletics/2013/0727/464961-barry-claims-discus-silver-at-ipc-worlds/|title=Orla Barry claims discus silver at IPC World Athletics Championships|work=rte.ie|accessdate=26 October 2016|date=27 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027054829/http://www.rte.ie/sport/athletics/2013/0727/464961-barry-claims-discus-silver-at-ipc-worlds/|archive-date=27 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Two years later in Doha, Saifi claimed her third consecutive World [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's discus throw|discus]] title in her class.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\nIn preparation for the Paralympics, she was trained by Hocine Saadoun for three hours a day, every day, except for weekends.<ref name=dz/>\nSaifi cemented her position as one of the greatest Paralympic competitors at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]] in Rio. Despite throwing well below her best (her winning throw being 33.33 metres) she was still able to take the gold medal, making her unbeaten at world and Paralympic level since 2011.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/> She also took silver in her less favoured shot put, her first at a Paralympics.<ref name=\"IPC Bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|687351}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saifi, Nassima}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Algeria]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Algerian female discus throwers]]\n[[Category:Algerian female shot putters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:People from Mila Province]]\n[[Category:African Games gold medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:African Games medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:African Games silver medalists for Algeria]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2015 African Games]]\n[[Category:World Para Athletics Championships winners]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassima_Saifi"}
{"title_page": "Pleuger rudder", "text_new": "[[File:Wiki Bild 01 Patent low.jpg|thumb|Device for propelling a ship patent]]\n\n{{short description|A thruster assisted ship's rudder}}\n{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bno-ip\\.</code> on the global blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=true}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{for|the Air Combat Maneuver known as Dutch Rudder|Thach Weave}}\nThe '''Pleuger rudder''' (also known as a '''Dutch rudder''') is a power assisted ship's [[rudder]].  It creates a flow of water in the direction the rudder points powered by an auxiliary electric motor. This aids maneuverability at low speeds greatly, since it operates on a similar principle to a [[Azimuth thruster|thruster]].\n\nA [[ducted propeller]] is mounted as an integral part of the rudder and is fixed to it. The duct is a [[Kort nozzle]] and enables the propeller to develop more thrust than an unducted propeller.\n\nThe Pleuger rudder is necessarily mounted in the flow from the main engine's propeller in a ship with an odd number of propellers. If the Pleuger and the main engine are run at the same time, the Pleuger can often be torn away.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html |quote=...the maiden voyage of the Elizabeth Bowater, which got off to a bad start (serves them right for sailing from Dundee on Friday 13th, June 1958) as the propeller for the Pleuger\"Activ\" rudder fell off while leaving the Caledon Shipyard in Dundee. |title=m.s Elizabeth Bowater |publisher=The Bowater Steamship Company |accessdate=17 October 2010}}</ref> The thrust produced by the Pleuger rudder is sufficient to power the ship in slow speed maneuvers when the force required to move the vessel is relatively small.\nThe Pleuger rudder is meant to be assisting in the fast maneuverability of ships, in tight harbor operations. Thus, it is only an improvement of rudder by controlling the water flow pattern passing a rudder and thus giving it an artificial flow and thus an extra power to steer even in slow engine r.p.m. It is absolutely not a substitute for a propeller, without which the mammoth energy required to propel a ship through the water is hard to generate.\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Azipod}}\n*{{annotated link|Kitchen rudder}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html  m.s Elizabeth Bowater which is fitted with a Pleuger rudder]\n*[http://www.flowserve.com/vgnfiles/Files/Literature/ProductLiterature/Pumps/pss-90-8.1-e.pdf Pleuger today]\n*[http://www.marineengineering.org.uk/navarch/navrudmain.htm Marine engineering -- Steering Gear -- Rudder types]\n\n[[Category:Propellers]]\n[[Category:Marine propulsion]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wiki Bild 01 Patent low.jpg|thumb|Device for propelling a ship patent]]\n\n{{short description|A thruster assisted ship's rudder}}\n{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bno-ip\\.</code> on the global blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=true}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{for|the Air Combat Maneuver known as Dutch Rudder|Thach Weave}}\nThe '''Pleuger rudder''' (also known as a '''Dutch rudder''') is a power assisted ship's [[rudder]].  It creates a flow of water in the direction the rudder points powered by an auxiliary electric motor. This aids maneuverability at low speeds greatly, since it operates on a similar principle to a [[Azimuth thruster|thruster]].\n\nA [[ducted propeller]] is mounted as an integral part of the rudder and is fixed to it. The duct is a [[Kort nozzle]] and enables the propeller to develop more thrust than an unducted propeller.\n\nThe Pleuger rudder is necessarily mounted in the flow from the main engine's propeller in a ship with an odd number of propellers. If the Pleuger and the main engine are run at the same time, the Pleuger can often be torn away.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html |quote=...the maiden voyage of the Elizabeth Bowater, which got off to a bad start (serves them right for sailing from Dundee on Friday 13th, June 1958) as the propeller for the Pleuger\"Activ\" rudder fell off while leaving the Caledon Shipyard in Dundee. |title=m.s Elizabeth Bowater |publisher=The Bowater Steamship Company |accessdate=17 October 2010}}</ref> The thrust produced by the Pleuger rudder is sufficient to power the ship in slow speed maneuvers when the force required to move the vessel is relatively small.\nThe Pleuger rudder is meant to be assisting in the fast maneuverability of ships, in tight harbor operations. Thus, it is only an improvement of rudder by controlling the water flow pattern passing a rudder and thus giving it an artificial flow and thus an extra power to steer even in slow engine r.p.m. It is absolutely not a substitute for a propeller, without which the mammoth energy required to make a ship move over water is hard to generate.\n\n==See also==\n*{{annotated link|Azipod}}\n*{{annotated link|Kitchen rudder}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bowatersteamshipcompany.no-ip.com/page13.html  m.s Elizabeth Bowater which is fitted with a Pleuger rudder]\n*[http://www.flowserve.com/vgnfiles/Files/Literature/ProductLiterature/Pumps/pss-90-8.1-e.pdf Pleuger today]\n*[http://www.marineengineering.org.uk/navarch/navrudmain.htm Marine engineering -- Steering Gear -- Rudder types]\n\n[[Category:Propellers]]\n[[Category:Marine propulsion]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamics]]\n", "name_user": "Arrivisto", "label": "safe", "comment": "wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pleuger_rudder"}
{"title_page": "Elections in Cyprus", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Update|date=March 2013}}\n{{Essay-like|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Politics of Cyprus}}\n'''Elections in Cyprus''' gives information on [[election]] and election results in [[politics of Cyprus|Cyprus]].\n\n==Elections==\n[[Cyprus]] elects on national level a [[head of state]] - the [[President (government title)|president]] -  and a [[legislature]]. The election of the President is [[Direct election|direct]], by [[universal suffrage]] and [[secret ballot]]. The president is elected for a five-year term by the people. The election of a new President takes place before the expiration of the five-year period of office of the outgoing President so as to enable the newly elected President to be invested on the date that period expires.\n\nElections are managed by the Central Elections Office which is part of the Ministry of Interior. The Permanent Secretary of the MoI serves as the General Returning Officer (GRO). At the district level, the permanent chief district officers act as District Returning Officers.\n\nVoting was [[Compulsory voting|compulsory]] and every citizen over the age of 18 had to vote, by law. On May 31, 2017, the cabinet approved a bill abolishing compulsory voting in elections, formally ending a law that has been inactive for years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2017/05/31/government-abolishes-compulsory-voting/|title=Government abolishes compulsory voting|date=May 31, 2017|publisher=Cyprus Mail}}</ref>\n\nCandidates for election must be citizens of the Republic of Cyprus and over 35 years of age.\nIf there is only one candidate for election, he is declared elected.\n\nA candidate to be elected needs more than 50% of the votes validly cast. If none of the candidates attains the required majority the election is repeated on the corresponding day of the following week between the two candidates who received the greater number of votes. The candidate who receives the greatest number of votes at these repeated elections is deemed elected.\n\nIf there is a vacancy in the office of Presidential, the vacancy is filled by a by-election taking place within a period not exceeding 45 days of the occurrence of such a vacancy.\n\nIn the event of a temporary absence or incapacity of the President to perform his duties, the President of the House of Representatives acts for him.\n\nThe [[House of Representatives of Cyprus|House of Representatives]] (''Vouli Antipros\u00f3pon/Temsilciler Meclisi'') has 59 members elected for a five-year term, 56 members  by [[proportional representation]] and 3 observer members representing the [[Maronite]], [[Roman-Catholic]] and [[Armenians|Armenian]] minorities. 24 seats are allocated to the Turkish community. \nCyprus has a [[multi-party]] system, with two or three strong [[political parties|parties]] and a third party that is electorally successful.\n\nAccording to article 62(1) of the Constitution the number of representatives is 50. Out of this number 35 are elected by the [[Greek Cypriot]] Community and 15 by the [[Turkish Cypriot]] Community. The Turkish Cypriot seats remain vacant since 1964 when the Turkish Cypriot representatives withdrew from the House.\n\nHowever, for the smooth running of the House of Representatives and of the Committees in particular, the House decided in July 1985 by adopting law 124, to increase the seats to 80. Of these 56 (70%) representatives are elected by the Greek Cypriot Community and 24 (30%) by the Turkish Cypriot Community, as provided in article 62(2) of the Constitution.\n\n==Latest elections==\n\n===2018 presidential election===\n{{main|2018 Cypriot presidential election}}\n\n[[File:CypElec 2018.png|thumb|350px|right|A map of the first round's results.]]\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!colspan=2 rowspan=2|Candidate\n!rowspan=2|Party\n!colspan=2|First round \n!colspan=2|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Democratic Rally/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Nicos Anastasiades]]||align=left|[[Democratic Rally]]||137,268||35.51||215,281||55.99\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Progressive Party of Working People/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Stavros Malas]]||align=left|[[Progressive Party of Working People]]||116,920||30.24||169,243||44.01\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Democratic Party (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Nikolas Papadopoulos]]||align=left|[[Democratic Party (Cyprus)|Democratic Party]]||99,508||25.74||colspan=2 rowspan=7|\n|-\n|bgcolor={{ELAM (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|Christos Christou||align=left|[[ELAM (Cyprus)|ELAM]]||21,846||5.65\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Citizens' Alliance (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Giorgos Lillikas]]||align=left|[[Citizens' Alliance (Cyprus)|Citizens' Alliance]]||8,419||2.18\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Andreas Efstratiou||align=left|Independent||845||0.22\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Charis Aristeidou||align=left|Independent||752||0.19\n|-\n| ||align=left|Michail Mina||align=left|Organisation of Justice Fighters ||662||0.17\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Christakis Kapiliotis||align=left|Independent||391||0.10\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Invalid/blank votes||9,338||\u2013||22,951||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|'''Total'''||'''395,949'''||'''100'''||'''407,475'''||'''100'''\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Registered voters/turnout||550,876||71.88||550,876||73.97\n|-\n|align=left colspan=7|Source: [http://europeanpolling.com/election-result-cyprus-presidency-2018-first-round European Polling Report], [http://www.ekloges.gov.cy/English/ Central Electoral Service]\n|}\n\n===2016 legislative election===\n{{main| 2016 Cypriot legislative election}}\n{{2016 Cypriot legislative election}}\n\n===2013 presidential election===\n{{main| 2013 Cypriot presidential election, 2013}}\n{{Cypriot presidential election}}\n\n==Past elections==\n\nThe British colonial administration drafted a constitution for Cyprus a few years after Cyprus was bought from the [[Ottomans]] (1878). The legislative assembly was to have 9 [[Greek Cypriot]] members, 3 [[Turkish Cypriot]] members (all elected) and 6 [[United Kingdom|British]] ex officio members. The vote of the British head of the assembly weighted more in case of a 50%-50% disagreement. Thus traditionally the Turkish Cypriot and British members would cooperate and pass legislation despite the disagreements of the [[Greek Cypriot]] members. In 1931 Necati Bey, a Turkish Cypriot supporter of [[Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] was elected (in previous years Turkish Cypriot members were hailed from the Ottoman ruling class). Necati Bey agreed with the Greek Cypriot members on several issues. This made the British governor, [[Sir Ronald Storrs]] to ignore the assembly when passing the bills. Angry Greek Cypriot members started a riot and the constitution was abolished.\n\nThe first municipal elections happened in 1943. Two of the winning mayors were members of [[AKEL]]: [[Ploutis Servas]] in [[Limassol]] and Adam Adamantos in [[Famagusta]], and the other six where Greek [[nationalism|nationalists]]. In 1946 the situation was reversed: 6 were either members or supported by AKEL, including Ioannis Klerides in [[Nicosia]].\n\n===Presidential elections===\nThe first presidential elections for independent Cyprus took place in 1960. The bulk of [[EOKA]] supporters were in favour of [[Makarios III]], whereas AKEL backed Ioannis Kleridis (father of [[Glafkos Klerides]]). Klerides was also backed by independent politicians, both left wingers  like [[Ploutis Servas]] and right wingers like Themistoklis Dervis. The Turkish Cypriot community elected  [[Fazil K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck]] for the position of vice president unopposed.\n\nThe next elections were due in 1965, but were postponed as a result of the extraordinary situation created by the intercommunal strife. The term of office was extended by a law of the House of Representatives.\n\nPresident Makarios distanced himself from his earlier ''enosis'' convictions in his 1968 presidential campaign and argued for the independence of Cyprus. He declared that [[Enosis]] was wishable but independence was possible. His opponent was the psychiatrist Takis Evdokas who was campaigning for Enosis. Makarios won the election. Turkish Cypriots were not participating in the government (see [[Cyprus dispute]]) but they had separate elections were Fazil K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck was reelected as vice president.\n\nIn 1973, Makarios was reelected unopposed.\n\nFollowing the death of Makarios in 1977, the then President of the House of Representatives, Spyros Kyprianou, assumed duties temporarily until 1978 elections.\n\nIn the 1978 election, Glafkos Klerides was backed by his party, [[Democratic Rally]] whereas [[Spyros Kyprianou]] was backed by the other Greek Cypriot parties. Following the kidnapping of Kyprianou's son, Achilleas, Klerides did not run for the election and Kyprianou won.\n\nIn 1983, Kyprianou's [[Democratic Party (Cyprus)|Democratic Party]] forged an alliance with AKEL based on an agreed agenda: the so-called minimum program. Kyprianou was reelected in the presidential elections of that year. He was opposed by Glafcos Clerides, the leader of the right-wing Democratic Rally party and Vassos Lyssarides of the [[Socialist]] party, EDEK.\n\nBy 1985, AKEL was not satisfied with Kyprianou's policies, especially his position in negotiations (see [[Cyprus dispute]] for more) and the partnership collapsed. AKEL found its new candidate for the 1988 election in [[George Vasiliou]] who managed to get to the second round of elections together with Glafkos Klerides. Kyprianou did not get enough votes. With the added support of [[Movement for Social Democracy|EDEK]], whose candidate Vasos Lyssaridis did not do very well in the first round, Vasiliou won the second round.\n\nWhile the Democratic Rally had been supporting Vasiliou in negotiating the [[Boutros Boutros-Ghali|Ghali]] set of ideas, as the 1993 elections were approaching it started criticising Vasiliou for not demanding enough. At the same time a partnership of Kyprianou's democratic party and Lyssaridis's EDEK was rejecting the spirit of the Ghali ideas all together and argued that both Vasiliou and Klerides were equally willing to compromise. The partnership received strong support by the [[Church of Cyprus|Church]] and its candidate was Paschalis Paschalidis.\n\nPaschalidis did not make it to the second round, however the democratic party made an agreement with Klerides and supported him. Thus Klerides was elected in 1993,defeating George Vassiliou, who again ran as an Independent candidate supported by AKEL and ADISOK, forming a government with members of both Democratic Rally and the Democratic Party.\n\nThe main issue of the 1998 election campaign was the purchase of S-300 antiaircraft missiles from [[Russia]]. Klerides was backed by EDEK whereas the democratic party and AKEL were backing George Iacovou, ex minister in the Kyprianou and Vasiliou governments. Klerides won the election.\n\nFor the 2003 election, EDEK leader Yiannakis Omirou declared himself candidate and the democratic rally initially backed him. Because of the course of negotiations Clerides asked to remain president for another couple of years, so the democratic rally backed him. This made EDEK turn to the opposition coalition already formed between AKEL and Democratic Party. The leader of the latter, [[Tassos Papadopoulos]] was chosen as a candidate. In the meantime the attorney general Alekos Markides disagreed with his party, Democratic Rally and ran as an independent candidate. \nPapadopoulos won from the first round.\n\n===Parliamentary elections===\nThe 1960 parliamentary elections were contested by three parties and a number of independent candidates. The right-wing \"Patriot Front\" won 30 seats, [[left-wing]] AKEL won five seats while the Pancyprian Union of Fighters did not win any seats.  No parliamentary elections were held in 1965 because of the prevailing intercommunal tension.\n\nFive parties contested the 5 July 1970 elections. Three of these, the Unified Party, the Progressive Front, and the opposition Democratic National Party, were [[right-wing]]; one, the Unified Democratic Union of Centre (EDEK), of the centre; and the other, AKEL, left-wing.\n\nThe third parliamentary elections took place on 5 September 1976, two years after the Turkish invasion. It was contested by the Democratic Rally, the Democratic Front (Democratic Party), [[socialist]] EDEK and left-wing AKEL. The right-wing Democratic Rally received about 26% of the votes, but due to a coalition ranged against it, was left with no Deputies.\n\nThe fourth parliamentary elections took place on 24 May 1981. The elections were contested by the right-wing Democratic Rally, the centre Democratic Party, the New Democratic Front and the Union of Centre, socialist EDEK and left-wing AKEL and PAME.\n\nIn the above election, a type of proportional system with threshold was used.\n\nThe fifth parliamentary elections took place on 8 December 1985. Following a law passed by the House of Representatives the number of seats allocated to the Greek Cypriot community was increased from 35 to 56. The number of Turkish Cypriot seats was raised from 15 to 24.\n\nThe elections were contested by four parties - the right-wing Democratic Rally, the centre Democratic Party, the socialist EDEK and left-wing AKEL - as well as independent candidates.\n\nVassos Lyssarides, leader of socialist party EDEK, was elected House President. His candidature was supported by his party and by the Democratic Party.\n\nThe sixth parliamentary elections took place on 19 May 1991. They were contested by the following political parties or party groupings - the Democratic Rally Party in coalition with the Liberal Party, the Democratic Party, the Socialist Party EDEK, AKEL-Left-New Forces Party and two new parties the Refugee Movement (PAKOP) and the Reformed Left (ADISOK), a splinter group from AKEL.\n\nAlexis Galanos (Democratic Party) was elected House President with the joint votes of the Democratic Party and the Democratic Rally - Liberals coalition.\n\nThe seventh parliamentary elections took place on 26 May 1996. They were held under a newly adopted system of [[proportional representation]] according to which a party receiving 1/56 of the valid votes or (1,79%) elected a House member. The new voting system encouraged the participation of more parties in the elections. The following political parties took part in the 1996 elections - the Democratic Rally - Liberal Party coalition, the New Horizons Party, the Democratic Party, the Movement of Free Democrats (of former President Vassiliou), the Ecologist Movement, the Socialist Party EDEK, the new Left (ADISOK) and the AKEL-Left-New Forces Party.\n\nSpyros Kyprianou was elected House President.\n\n==Referendums==\n[[Constitution of Cyprus]] has no mention of referendum (as of 2013).<ref name=\"text\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.gov.cy/presidency/presidency.nsf/all/1003AEDD83EED9C7C225756F0023C6AD/$file/CY_Constitution.pdf?openelement|title=Cyprus Constitution|accessdate=2013-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103050430/http://www.presidency.gov.cy/presidency/presidency.nsf/all/1003AEDD83EED9C7C225756F0023C6AD/$file/CY_Constitution.pdf?openelement|archive-date=2013-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cyprus is one of only two states not to hold the referendum on joining the [[European Union]] (the other being the [[United Kingdom]]). The only referendum to take place in independent Cyprus was [[2004 Cypriot Annan Plan referendums|a referendum on the Annan Plan]] which was held both in the Republic of Cyprus and the breakaway [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]] on 24 April 2004. Before Cypriot independence there was also a [[1950 Cypriot Enosis referendum|Cypriot Enosis referendum]] in 1950, which was unofficial and was held in Greek Orthodox churches.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral calendar]]\n* [[Electoral system]]\n* [[Politics of Cyprus]]\n* [[House of Representatives of Cyprus]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090527075708/http://www.kyproekloges.com/ Cyprus Elections by KyproEkloges.com]\n*[http://www.cypruselections.org/ Cyprus Elections & Politics]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/c/cyprus/ Adam Carr's Election Archive]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/n/northcyprus/ Adam Carr's Election Archive (North Cyprus)]\n\n{{Cypriot elections}}\n{{Asia topic|Elections in}}\n{{Elections in Europe}}\n{{Cyprus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Elections in Cyprus| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Update|date=March 2013}}\n{{Essay-like|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Politics of Cyprus}}\n'''Elections in Cyprus''' gives information on [[election]] and election results in [[politics of Cyprus|Cyprus]].\n\n==Elections==\n[[Cyprus]] elects on national level a [[head of state]] - the [[President (government title)|president]] -  and a [[legislature]]. The election of the President is [[Direct election|direct]], by [[universal suffrage]] and [[secret ballot]]. The president is elected for a five-year term by the people. The election of a new President takes place before the expiration of the five-year period of office of the outgoing President so as to enable the newly elected President to be invested on the date that period expires.\n\nElections are managed by the Central Elections Office which is part of the Ministry of Interior. The Permanent Secretary of the MoI serves as the General Returning Officer (GRO). At the district level, the permanent chief district officers act as District Returning Officers.\n\nVoting was [[Compulsory voting|compulsory]] and every citizen over the age of 18 had to vote, by law. On May 31, 2017, the cabinet approved a bill abolishing compulsory voting in elections, formally ending a law that has been inactive for years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2017/05/31/government-abolishes-compulsory-voting/|title=Government abolishes compulsory voting|date=May 31, 2017|publisher=Cyprus Mail}}</ref>\n\nCandidates for election must be citizens of the Republic of Cyprus and over 35 years of age.\nIf there is only one candidate for election, he is declared elected.\n\nA candidate to be elected needs more than 50% of the votes validly cast. If none of the candidates attains the required majority the election is repeated on the corresponding day of the following week between the two candidates who received the greater number of votes. The candidate who receives the greatest number of votes at these repeated elections is deemed elected.\n\nIf there is a vacancy in the office of Presidential, the vacancy is filled by a by-election taking place within a period not exceeding 45 days of the occurrence of such a vacancy.\n\nIn the event of a temporary absence or incapacity of the President to perform his duties, the President of the House of Representatives acts for him.\n\nThe [[House of Representatives of Cyprus|House of Representatives]] (''Vouli Antipros\u00f3pon/Temsilciler Meclisi'') has 59 members elected for a five-year term, 56 members  by [[proportional representation]] and 3 observer members representing the [[Maronite]], [[Roman-Catholic]] and [[Armenians|Armenian]] minorities. 24 seats are allocated to the Turkish community. \nCyprus has a [[multi-party]] system, with two or three strong [[political parties|parties]] and a third party that is electorally successful.\n\nAccording to article 62(1) of the Constitution the number of representatives is 50. Out of this number 35 are elected by the [[Greek Cypriot]] Community and 15 by the [[Turkish Cypriot]] Community. The Turkish Cypriot seats remain vacant since 1964 when the Turkish Cypriot representatives withdrew from the House.\n\nHowever, for the smooth running of the House of Representatives and of the Committees in particular, the House decided in July 1985 by adopting law 124, to increase the seats to 80. Of these 56 (70%) representatives are elected by the Greek Cypriot Community and 24 (30%) by the Turkish Cypriot Community, as provided in article 62(2) of the Constitution.\n\n==Latest elections==\n\n===2018 presidential election===\n{{main|2018 Cypriot presidential election}}\n\n[[File:CypElec 2018.png|thumb|350px|right|A map of the first round's results.]]\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!colspan=2 rowspan=2|Candidate\n!rowspan=2|Party\n!colspan=2|First round \n!colspan=2|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Democratic Rally/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Nicos Anastasiades]]||align=left|[[Democratic Rally]]||137,268||35.51||215,281||55.99\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Progressive Party of Working People/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Stavros Malas]]||align=left|[[Progressive Party of Working People]]||116,920||30.24||169,243||44.01\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Democratic Party (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Nikolas Papadopoulos]]||align=left|[[Democratic Party (Cyprus)|Democratic Party]]||99,508||25.74||colspan=2 rowspan=7|\n|-\n|bgcolor={{ELAM (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|Christos Christou||align=left|[[ELAM (Cyprus)|ELAM]]||21,846||5.65\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Citizens' Alliance (Cyprus)/meta/color}}|\n|align=left|[[Giorgos Lillikas]]||align=left|[[Citizens' Alliance (Cyprus)|Citizens' Alliance]]||8,419||2.18\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Andreas Efstratiou||align=left|Independent||845||0.22\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Charis Aristeidou||align=left|Independent||752||0.19\n|-\n| ||align=left|Michail Mina||align=left|Organisation of Justice Fighters ||662||0.17\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}| ||align=left|Christakis Kapiliotis||align=left|Independent||391||0.10\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Invalid/blank votes||9,338||\u2013||22,951||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|'''Total'''||'''395,949'''||'''100'''||'''407,475'''||'''100'''\n|-\n|align=left colspan=3|Registered voters/turnout||550,876||71.88||550,876||73.97\n|-\n|align=left colspan=7|Source: [http://europeanpolling.com/election-result-cyprus-presidency-2018-first-round European Polling Report], [http://www.ekloges.gov.cy/English/ Central Electoral Service]\n|}\n\n===2016 legislative election===\n{{main| 2016 Cypriot legislative election}}\n{{2016 Cypriot legislative election}}\n\n===2013 presidential election===\n{{main| 2013 Cypriot presidential election, 2013}}\n{{Cypriot presidential election}}\n\n==Past elections==\n\nThe British colonial administration drafted a constitution for Cyprus a few years after Cyprus was bought from the [[Ottomans]] (1878). The legislative assembly was to have 9 [[Greek Cypriot]] members, 3 [[Turkish Cypriot]] members (all elected) and 6 [[United Kingdom|British]] ex officio members. The vote of the British head of the assembly weighted more in case of a 50%-50% disagreement. Thus traditionally the Turkish Cypriot and British members would cooperate and pass legislation despite the disagreements of the [[Greek Cypriot]] members. In 1931 Necati Bey, a Turkish Cypriot supporter of [[Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] was elected (in previous years Turkish Cypriot members were hailed from the Ottoman ruling class). Necati Bey agreed with the Greek Cypriot members on several issues. This made the British governor, [[Sir Ronald Storrs]] to ignore the assembly when passing the bills. Angry Greek Cypriot members started a riot and the constitution was abolished.\n\nThe first municipal elections happened in 1943. Two of the winning mayors were members of [[AKEL]]: [[Ploutis Servas]] in [[Limassol]] and Adam Adamantos in [[Famagusta]], and the other six where Greek [[nationalism|nationalists]]. In 1946 the situation was reversed: 6 were either members or supported by AKEL, including Ioannis Klerides in [[Nicosia]].\n\n===Presidential elections===\nThe first presidential elections for independent Cyprus took place in 1960. The bulk of [[EOKA]] supporters were in favour of [[Makarios III]], whereas AKEL backed Ioannis Kleridis (father of [[Glafkos Klerides]]). Klerides was also backed by independent politicians, both left wingers  like [[Ploutis Servas]] and right wingers like Themistoklis Dervis. The Turkish Cypriot community elected  [[Fazil K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck]] for the position of vice president unopposed.\n\nThe next elections were due in 1965, but were postponed as a result of the extraordinary situation created by the intercommunal strife. The term of office was extended by a law of the House of Representatives.\n\nPresident Makarios distanced himself from his earlier ''enosis'' convictions in his 1968 presidential campaign and argued for the independence of Cyprus. He declared that [[Enosis]] was wishable but independence was possible. His opponent was the psychiatrist Takis Evdokas who was campaigning for Enosis. Makarios won the election. Turkish Cypriots were not participating in the government (see [[Cyprus dispute]]) but they had separate elections were Fazil K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck was reelected as vice president.\n\nIn 1973, Makarios was reelected unopposed.\n\nFollowing the death of Makarios in 1977, the then President of the House of Representatives, Spyros Kyprianou, assumed duties temporarily until 1978 elections.\n\nIn the 1978 election, Glafkos Klerides was backed by his party, [[Democratic Rally]] whereas [[Spyros Kyprianou]] was backed by the other Greek Cypriot parties. Following the kidnapping of Kyprianou's son, Achilleas, Klerides did not run for the election and Kyprianou won.\n\nIn 1983, Kyprianou's [[Democratic Party (Cyprus)|Democratic Party]] forged an alliance with AKEL based on an agreed agenda: the so-called minimum program. Kyprianou was reelected in the presidential elections of that year. He was opposed by Glafcos Clerides, the leader of the right-wing Democratic Rally party and Vassos Lyssarides of the [[Socialist]] party, EDEK.\n\nBy 1985, AKEL was not satisfied with Kyprianou's policies, especially his position in negotiations (see [[Cyprus dispute]] for more) and the partnership collapsed. AKEL found its new candidate for the 1988 election in [[George Vasiliou]] who managed to get to the second round of elections together with Glafkos Klerides. Kyprianou did not get enough votes. With the added support of [[Movement for Social Democracy|EDEK]], whose candidate Vasos Lyssaridis did not do very well in the first round, Vasiliou won the second round.\n\nWhile the Democratic Rally had been supporting Vasiliou in negotiating the [[Boutros Boutros-Ghali|Ghali]] set of ideas, as the 1993 elections were approaching it started criticising Vasiliou for not demanding enough. At the same time a partnership of Kyprianou's democratic party and Lyssaridis's EDEK was rejecting the spirit of the Ghali ideas all together and argued that both Vasiliou and Klerides were equally willing to compromise. The partnership received strong support by the [[Church of Cyprus|Church]] and its candidate was Paschalis Paschalidis.\n\nPaschalidis didn't make it to the second round, however the democratic party made an agreement with Klerides and supported him. Thus Klerides was elected in 1993,defeating George Vassiliou, who again ran as an Independent candidate supported by AKEL and ADISOK, forming a government with members of both Democratic Rally and the Democratic Party.\n\nThe main issue of the 1998 election campaign was the purchase of S-300 antiaircraft missiles from [[Russia]]. Klerides was backed by EDEK whereas the democratic party and AKEL were backing George Iacovou, ex minister in the Kyprianou and Vasiliou governments. Klerides won the election.\n\nFor the 2003 election, EDEK leader Yiannakis Omirou declared himself candidate and the democratic rally initially backed him. Because of the course of negotiations Clerides asked to remain president for another couple of years, so the democratic rally backed him. This made EDEK turn to the opposition coalition already formed between AKEL and Democratic Party. The leader of the latter, [[Tassos Papadopoulos]] was chosen as a candidate. In the meantime the attorney general Alekos Markides disagreed with his party, Democratic Rally and ran as an independent candidate. \nPapadopoulos won from the first round.\n\n===Parliamentary elections===\nThe 1960 parliamentary elections were contested by three parties and a number of independent candidates. The right-wing \"Patriot Front\" won 30 seats, [[left-wing]] AKEL won five seats while the Pancyprian Union of Fighters did not win any seats.  No parliamentary elections were held in 1965 because of the prevailing intercommunal tension.\n\nFive parties contested the 5 July 1970 elections. Three of these, the Unified Party, the Progressive Front, and the opposition Democratic National Party, were [[right-wing]]; one, the Unified Democratic Union of Centre (EDEK), of the centre; and the other, AKEL, left-wing.\n\nThe third parliamentary elections took place on 5 September 1976, two years after the Turkish invasion. It was contested by the Democratic Rally, the Democratic Front(Democratic Party), [[socialist]] EDEK and left-wing AKEL. The right-wing Democratic Rally received about 26% of the votes, but due to a coalition ranged against it, was left with no Deputies.\n\nThe fourth parliamentary elections took place on 24 May 1981. The elections were contested by the right-wing Democratic Rally, the centre Democratic Party, the New Democratic Front and the Union of Centre, socialist EDEK and left-wing AKEL and PAME.\n\nIn the above election, a type of proportional system with threshold was used.\n\nThe fifth parliamentary elections took place on 8 December 1985. Following a law passed by the House of Representatives the number of seats allocated to the Greek Cypriot community was increased from 35 to 56. The number of Turkish Cypriot seats was raised from 15 to 24.\n\nThe elections were contested by four parties - the right-wing Democratic Rally, the centre Democratic Party, the socialist EDEK and left-wing AKEL - as well as independent candidates.\n\nVassos Lyssarides, leader of socialist party EDEK, was elected House President. His candidature was supported by his party and by the Democratic Party.\n\nThe sixth parliamentary elections took place on 19 May 1991. They were contested by the following political parties or party groupings - the Democratic Rally Party in coalition with the Liberal Party, the Democratic Party, the Socialist Party EDEK, AKEL-Left-New Forces Party and two new parties the Refugee Movement (PAKOP) and the Reformed Left (ADISOK), a splinter group from AKEL.\n\nAlexis Galanos (Democratic Party) was elected House President with the joint votes of the Democratic Party and the Democratic Rally - Liberals coalition.\n\nThe seventh parliamentary elections took place on 26 May 1996. They were held under a newly adopted system of [[proportional representation]] according to which a party receiving 1/56 of the valid votes or (1,79%) elected a House member. The new voting system encouraged the participation of more parties in the elections. The following political parties took part in the 1996 elections - the Democratic Rally - Liberal Party coalition, the New Horizons Party, the Democratic Party, the Movement of Free Democrats (of former President Vassiliou), the Ecologist Movement, the Socialist Party EDEK, the new Left (ADISOK) and the AKEL-Left-New Forces Party.\n\nSpyros Kyprianou was elected House President.\n\n==Referendums==\n[[Constitution of Cyprus]] has no mention of referendum (as of 2013).<ref name=\"text\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.gov.cy/presidency/presidency.nsf/all/1003AEDD83EED9C7C225756F0023C6AD/$file/CY_Constitution.pdf?openelement|title=Cyprus Constitution|accessdate=2013-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103050430/http://www.presidency.gov.cy/presidency/presidency.nsf/all/1003AEDD83EED9C7C225756F0023C6AD/$file/CY_Constitution.pdf?openelement|archive-date=2013-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cyprus is one of only two states not to hold the referendum on joining the [[European Union]] (the other being the [[United Kingdom]]). The only referendum to take place in independent Cyprus was [[2004 Cypriot Annan Plan referendums|a referendum on the Annan Plan]] which was held both in the Republic of Cyprus and the breakaway [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]] on 24 April 2004. Before Cypriot independence there was also a [[1950 Cypriot Enosis referendum|Cypriot Enosis referendum]] in 1950, which was unofficial and was held in Greek Orthodox churches.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral calendar]]\n* [[Electoral system]]\n* [[Politics of Cyprus]]\n* [[House of Representatives of Cyprus]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090527075708/http://www.kyproekloges.com/ Cyprus Elections by KyproEkloges.com]\n*[http://www.cypruselections.org/ Cyprus Elections & Politics]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/c/cyprus/ Adam Carr's Election Archive]\n*[http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/n/northcyprus/ Adam Carr's Election Archive (North Cyprus)]\n\n{{Cypriot elections}}\n{{Asia topic|Elections in}}\n{{Elections in Europe}}\n{{Cyprus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Elections in Cyprus| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a typo and a contraction found withWikipedia:Typo_Team/moss.  Please seeMOS::CONTRACTION.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elections_in_Cyprus"}
