cs         = \n| conference        = [[Monsignor Martin Athletic Association]]\n| slogan            =  \n| song              = [[When The Saints Go Marching In]]\n| fightsong         = \n| motto             = Signum Fidei\n| motto_translation = ''Sign of Faith''\n| accreditation     = [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=\"MSA-Commission on Secondary Schools\">{{cite web|url=http://www.css-msa.org/search.php/|title=MSA-Commission on Secondary Schools|access-date=2009-05-27|author=MSA-CSS|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917141934/http://www.css-msa.org/search.php/|archive-date=2009-09-17|df=}}</ref>\n| rival             = [[Canisius High School]]\n| mascot            = Masked Marauder\n| mascot image      = \n| sports            = Volleyball, Football, Soccer, Golf, Track and Field, Indoor Track, Cross Country, Hockey, Bowling, Basketball, Baseball, Swimming, Sailing, Squash, Rowing, Wrestling, Tennis and Lacrosse.\n| patron            = St. [[Jean-Baptiste de La Salle]]\n| team_name         = Marauders\n| nickname          = \n| colors            = [[Maroon (color)|Maroon]], [[Silver (color)|Silver]], and [[White]] {{Color box|Maroon}}{{Color box|Silver}}{{Color box|White}}\n| yearbook          = ''Star''\n| publication       = ''The Collegiate''\n| newspaper         = ''The Student Prints''\n| established       = 1861\n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   = \n| enrollment        = 630<ref>https://www.sjci.com/apps/pages/fastfacts</ref>\n| enrollment_as_of  = 2019-2020\n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeders           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = Admissions Director\n| free_text2        = Peter Kennedy\n| free_label3       = Athletic Director\n| free_text3        = Brian Anken\n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = http://www.sjci.com/ \n}}\n\n'''St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute''', founded in 1861, is an independent [[Roman Catholic]] [[college preparatory]] school for young men. Established by the [[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|De La Salle Christian Brothers]], SJCI is chartered by the [[University of the State of New York|Board of Regents of New York State]] and accredited by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]. It is a member of the Christian Brothers' Education Association, The College Board, and the [[National Catholic Education Association]].  It is located in the town of [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda]].<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"buffalo ne quad\"/>\n\n==Mission==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2016}}\nSt. Joseph's Collegiate Institute is a Catholic, independent college-preparatory school educating young men of diverse backgrounds in the tradition of St. John Baptist de La Salle. Through a broad and balanced, human and Christian education, St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute guides the development of each student's unique talents, fostering a commitment to academic excellence, service, and leadership in the global community.\n\n==History==\n{{one source|section|date=April 2016}}\nThe History of St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute is predated by only a few years by that of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo]], which was established on April 23, 1847. Very Rev John Timon, named the first Bishop of Buffalo by [[Pope Pius IX]], was consecrated in [[St. Patrick's Old Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], New York City, on Sunday, October 17 and arrived in Buffalo on October 22, 1847.\n\nIn 1849, Bishop Timon moved into the Webster House on Franklin Street. Always concerned with vocations to the priesthood, he established in the rectory a [[seminary]] for three young men. The seminary was named St. Joseph's College because of a special veneration the bishop held for St. Joseph. Its early history was a varied one, as it moved from one location to another in several areas of the city.\n\nLater in 1850., Bishop Timon asked the [[Oblates of Mary Immaculate]] to staff the seminary in his residence. On July 2, 1851, the Oblates arrived and opened a school chartered on March 12, 1851 under the name \"The Buffalo College of St. Joseph,\" which Bishop Timon said, \"...exists for missionary and no other purpose.\" In August 1861, six Christian Brothers from New York and Montreal arrived in Buffalo and settled at 187 Terrace Street. Brother Crispian, Director of this first Christian Brothers' community in Buffalo, Brother Pompian (Sub-Director), Brothers Demedrian, Ptolemy, Benedict and one Brother whose religious name is unknown had come to the city in response to Bishop Timon's urgent plea for assistance in educating the Catholic youth of Buffalo.\n\nThe first building in which the Brothers taught was built by a local contractor, a Mr. Flanagan, at a cost of $7,000. Two departments were started in this first school on September 2, 1861: St. Joseph's Academy (a tuition school), with 130 boys registered, and St. Joseph's Free School, with 150 boys. The brick building was located opposite Union Terrace, which at that time was a beautiful park. The Free School was located on the first floor of the building, the Academy on the second floor., and the Brothers dormitory on the third floor. This building, later known as \"Old Cathedral Hall,\" was located at 1 Delaware Avenue.\n\nIn response to numerous requests from clergy and parents, and after being closed for two years, St. Joseph's College reopened in September 1893. Due to the railroad station at Union Terrace and the encroachment of business and manufacturing interests, the Delaware Avenue site was no longer a desirable one. For what they knew would be a temporary stay, the Brothers rented a two-story brick building at 473 Prospect Avenue near Jersey Street which housed about fifty pupils during each of the four years the school occupied it.\n\nIn 1945, plans were again taken up for the \"new St. Joe's\" on Kenmore Avenue. Brother Andrew of the Cross-sponsored a drive to secure funds to commence the project. The proposed plan was to include three buildings: a general school building to accommodate 900 students, a gymnasium with three basketball courts and a [[seating capacity]] of 2000, and a faculty house with accommodations for thirty brothers. In addition, there were to be football and baseball fields, a quarter-mile cinder track, and facilities for other sports.\n\nThe first classes were held in the new building on April 19, 1950. In the years to follow, the new facility allowed for increases in both the size of the student body and the number of faculty members. Such facilities as a drafting room, photographic darkroom and a soda fountain were appealing to the students. The school also featured, according to news accounts of the day, such modern innovations\" as a public address system linking the principal's office to all rooms of the school and green glass chalkboards, replacing the old familiar blackboards.\" The new building was dedicated on May 14, 1950.\n\nOn November 16, 2006, it was announced that [http://buffalonews.com/2006/11/16/2-million-gift-to-st-joes-once-reluctant-student-makes-record-donation-to-town-of-tonawanda-high-school/ alumnus Jack Cullen] had made a gift of $2 million to support construction of new science laboratories and classrooms, as well as the annual school musical. This gift, along with two other $1 million gifts from alumni, are the foundation for [http://www.sjci.com/capital-campaign-announced.php a $12 million capital campaign] announced on May 15, 2007, to build new science laboratories, an athletic complex, and a new residence for the Christian Brothers on campus, as well as increasing the endowment for financial aid.\n\n==Facilities==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2016}}\nThe campus of St. Joseph\u2019s Collegiate Institute (SJCI or St. Joe's) is located at 845 Kenmore Avenue in the town of [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda]]<ref name=\"USGS\">{{cite web|url=http://mapper.acme.com/?ll=42.95902,-78.84912&z=15&t=T&marker0=42.95902%2C-78.84912%2C845%20Kenmore%20Ave%5C%2C%20Buffalo%5C%2C%20NY|title=St. Joseph's collegiate Institute on USGS map|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"buffalo ne quad\">{{cite map|url=http://gis.ny.gov/gisdata/quads/drg24/dotpreview/index.cfm?code=q8 |title=Buffalo NE Digital Raster Quadrangle|publisher=New York State Department of Transportation|year=1989|scale=1:24,000|accessdate=January 22, 2010}}</ref> (near [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]) and rests on 11.9 acres (48,000 m\u00b2). There are three buildings on the grounds: the Academic Building, Field House, and Innovation Center. The Brothers Residence was torn down in 2008 and is now the site of The Cullen Center for Excellence in Science, which includes a new residence on the top floor.\n\nWithin St. Joseph\u2019s Collegiate Institute, there are two academic computer labs, a newly updated Computer Graphics Lab in the art wing, and a Music Lab that employs Mac and Windows computers. The library also contains workstations for internet access. The Fine Arts facility includes a fully functioning black-box theatre, band room and sound-proof practice facilities<ref>https://www.sjci.com/apps/pages/fastfacts</ref>.\n\nAthletics are also an integral part of the St. Joe\u2019s experience and students are able to take advantage of both indoor and outdoor facilities. A modern weight room, renovated in 2014, two gymnasiums, a field house, and the 183,961 square foot, all-weather artificial turf Robert T. Scott AFSC Athletic Field Complex comprise the facilities of the athletic department. The Cullen Center for Excellence in science building was finished in fall 2009 and is presently in use. Classes include lab stations, smartboards and a work area for each student.\n\n==Sports==\nSt. Joseph's Collegiate Institute offers an extensive athletic program consisting of 16 sports, with most sports offering multiple levels of competition.  St. Joe's has won the Supremacy Cup, recognizing the top overall athletic program in the [[Monsignor Martin Athletic Association]]'s AA League, 31 times in the 58 years of the league's existence.<ref>http://www.sjci.com/athletics.php</ref>\n\nIn addition to interscholastic competition, St. Joe's offers a number of intramural athletic programs and maintains a vocal group of student supporters at their major sports events.\n\nThe Marauders' main rival is [[Canisius High School]].\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Michael A. Caligiuri]] - noted cancer researcher and President & Physician-in-Chief, [[City of Hope National Medical Center]]\n*[[Craig Cirbus]] \u2013 former [[University at Buffalo]] head football coach\n* [[Jimmy Collins]] \u2013 first player selected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] primarily as a [[third baseman]]<ref>[http://www.gbshof.com/1993/jimmy_collins.html The Greater Buffalo Sports Hall of Fame: Jimmy Collins] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711080822/http://www.gbshof.com/1993/jimmy_collins.html |date=2011-07-11 }}</ref>\n* [[Don Criqui]] \u2013 football commentator for [[CBS Sports]] and the [[University of Notre Dame]] and member of the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]<ref>[http://www.gbshof.com/2003/don_criqui.html The Greater Buffalo Sports Hall of Fame: Don Criqui] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711080857/http://www.gbshof.com/2003/don_criqui.html |date=2011-07-11 }}</ref>\n* [[William Joseph Donovan|William \"Wild Bill\" Joseph Donovan]] \u2013 lawyer, general and founder of the [[Office of Strategic Services]], winner of the Congressional [[Medal of Honor]], \"founder\" of the [[CIA]]<ref>[http://www.samhoyt.com/index.php?src=news&refno=435&category=Press%20Releases Assemblymembers Sam Hoyt and Mark J.F. Schroeder honor the legacy of General William Donovan]</ref>\n* [[Eugene M. Fahey]] \u2013 Judge of the New York Court of Appeals<ref name=\"NYC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nycourts.gov/ctapps/jfahey.htm |title=Honorable Eugene M. Fahey |publisher=Nycourts.gov |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2017-10-05}}</ref>\n* [[Dennis Gilbert (ice hockey)]] \u2013 Professional ice hockey defenseman with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] of the [[National Hockey League]]<ref>https://www.hockey-reference.com/players/g/gilbede01.html</ref>\n* [[John Patrick Hopkins]] \u2013 mayor of Chicago (1893\u201395)\n* [[Chad Kelly]] \u2013 American football quarterback\n*[[David Leggio]] - Professional ice hockey goaltender and United States Olympian\n* [[Christopher Markus]] \u2013 [[Emmy Award]]-winning screenwriter, best known for [[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]], [[Captain America: The First Avenger]], [[The Life and Death of Peter Sellers]] and [[Avengers: Infinity War]] \n*[[Jaylen Morris]] - Professional basketball player who has played for the [[Atlanta Hawks]] and [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n* [[Vaughn Parker]] \u2013 former [[NFL]] [[tackle (American football position)|tackle]], [[San Diego Chargers]] and [[Washington Redskins]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaughn A. Parker \u201989 Addresses The Class Of 2006|url=http://www.sjci.com/ftp_only/myers/spring_2006vs2.pdf|format=PDF|work=The Collegiate|location=St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute|page=4|date=Spring 2006|access-date=May 18, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106152649/http://www.sjci.com/ftp_only/myers/spring_2006vs2.pdf|archive-date=January 6, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Paxon]] \u2013 [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]], 1989-99<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=p000148 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress: William L. Paxon], bioguide.congress.gov; accessed August 8, 2016.</ref>\n* [[Carmen A. Puliafito]] \u2013 Dean, Keck School of Medicine at the [[University of Southern California]] {{When|date=August 2016}}\n* [[James Edward Quigley]] \u2013 Archbishop of Chicago (1903\u201315)\n* [[Naaman Roosevelt]] \u2013 wide receiver, [[Buffalo Bills]] (2010\u201311) <ref>[http://www.nfl.com/player/naamanroosevelt/2507830/profile Naaman Roosevelt Profile], NFL.com; accessed February 28, 2018.</ref>\n* [[Sean Ryan (football player)|Sean Ryan]] \u2013 tight end, [[National Football League]]<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/player/seanryan/2506010/profile Sean Ryan Profile], NFL.com; accessed February 28, 2018.</ref> (2004\u201309)\n* [[Cole Schneider]] \u2013 hockey player, [[New York Rangers]]<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/player/cole-schneider-8476766 Cole Schneider profile], NHL.com; accessed August 8, 2016.</ref>\n* [[William F. Sheehan]] \u2013 Lawyer, politician; Lieutenant Governor of New York (1892\u201394)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.sjci.com/ St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute]\n\n{{Monsignor Martin Athletic Association}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo}}\n{{Boys' schools in New York State}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Joseph's Collegiate Institute}}\n[[Category:Lasallian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name              = Saint Joseph's Collegiate Institute \n\n| latin_name        =\n| image             = St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute logo.JPG\n| imagesize         = 150px\n| caption           = \n| location          = [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Town of Tonawanda]]\n| streetaddress     = 845 Kenmore Avenue\n| city              = [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Town of Tonawanda]]\n| state             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| county