ssociation of Colleges and Schools]]. It is a member of the Christian Brothers' Education Association, The College Board, and the [[National Catholic Education Association]].  It is located in the town of [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda]].<ref name=\"USGS\"/><ref name=\"buffalo ne quad\"/>\n\n==Mission==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2016}}\nSt. Joseph's Collegiate Institute is a Catholic, independent college-preparatory school educating young men of diverse backgrounds in the tradition of St. John Baptist de La Salle. Through a broad and balanced, human and Christian education, St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute guides the development of each student's unique talents, fostering a commitment to academic excellence, service, and leadership in the global community.\n\n==History==\n{{one source|section|date=April 2016}}\nThe History of St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute is predated by only a few years by that of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo]], which was established on April 23, 1847. Very Rev John Timon, named the first Bishop of Buffalo by [[Pope Pius IX]], was consecrated in [[St. Patrick's Old Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]], New York City, on Sunday, October 17 and arrived in Buffalo on October 22, 1847.\n\nIn 1849, Bishop Timon moved into the Webster House on Franklin Street. Always concerned with vocations to the priesthood, he established in the rectory a [[seminary]] for three young men. The seminary was named St. Joseph's College because of a special veneration the bishop held for St. Joseph. Its early history was a varied one, as it moved from one location to another in several areas of the city.\n\nLater in 1850., Bishop Timon asked the [[Oblates of Mary Immaculate]] to staff the seminary in his residence. On July 2, 1851, the Oblates arrived and opened a school chartered on March 12, 1851 under the name \"The Buffalo College of St. Joseph,\" which Bishop Timon said, \"...exists for missionary and no other purpose.\" In August 1861, six Christian Brothers from New York and Montreal arrived in Buffalo and settled at 187 Terrace Street. Brother Crispian, Director of this first Christian Brothers' community in Buffalo, Brother Pompian (Sub-Director), Brothers Demedrian, Ptolemy, Benedict and one Brother whose religious name is unknown had come to the city in response to Bishop Timon's urgent plea for assistance in educating the Catholic youth of Buffalo.\n\nThe first building in which the Brothers taught was built by a local contractor, a Mr. Flanagan, at a cost of $7,000. Two departments were started in this first school on September 2, 1861: St. Joseph's Academy (a tuition school), with 130 boys registered, and St. Joseph's Free School, with 150 boys. The brick building was located opposite Union Terrace, which at that time was a beautiful park. The Free School was located on the first floor of the building, the Academy on the second floor., and the Brothers dormitory on the third floor. This building, later known as \"Old Cathedral Hall,\" was located at 1 Delaware Avenue.\n\nIn response to numerous requests from clergy and parents, and after being closed for two years, St. Joseph's College reopened in September 1893. Due to the railroad station at Union Terrace and the encroachment of business and manufacturing interests, the Delaware Avenue site was no longer a desirable one. For what they knew would be a temporary stay, the Brothers rented a two-story brick building at 473 Prospect Avenue near Jersey Street which housed about fifty pupils during each of the four years the school occupied it.\n\nIn 1945, plans were again taken up for the \"new St. Joe's\" on Kenmore Avenue. Brother Andrew of the Cross-sponsored a drive to secure funds to commence the project. The proposed plan was to include three buildings: a general school building to accommodate 900 students, a gymnasium with three basketball courts and a [[seating capacity]] of 2000, and a faculty house with accommodations for thirty brothers. In addition, there were to be football and baseball fields, a quarter-mile cinder track, and facilities for other sports.\n\nThe first classes were held in the new building on April 19, 1950. In the years to follow, the new facility allowed for increases in both the size of the student body and the number of faculty members. Such facilities as a drafting room, photographic darkroom and a soda fountain were appealing to the students. The school also featured, according to news accounts of the day, such modern innovations\" as a public address system linking the principal's office to all rooms of the school and green glass chalkboards, replacing the old familiar blackboards.\" The new building was dedicated on May 14, 1950.\n\nOn November 16, 2006, it was announced that [http://buffalonews.com/2006/11/16/2-million-gift-to-st-joes-once-reluctant-student-makes-record-donation-to-town-of-tonawanda-high-school/ alumnus Jack Cullen] had made a gift of $2 million to support construction of new science laboratories and classrooms, as well as the annual school musical. This gift, along with two other $1 million gifts from alumni, are the foundation for [http://www.sjci.com/capital-campaign-announced.php a $12 million capital campaign] announced on May 15, 2007, to build new science laboratories, an athletic complex, and a new residence for the Christian Brothers on campus, as well as increasing the endowment for financial aid.\n\n==Facilities==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2016}}\nThe campus of St. Joseph\u2019s Collegiate Institute (SJCI or St. Joe's) is located at 845 Kenmore Avenue in the town of [[Tonawanda (town), New York|Tonawanda]]<ref name=\"USGS\">{{cite web|url=http://mapper.acme.com/?ll=42.95902,-78.84912&z=15&t=T&marker0=42.95902%2C-78.84912%2C845%20Kenmore%20Ave%5C%2C%20Buffalo%5C%2C%20NY|title=St. Joseph's collegiate Institute on USGS map|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"buffalo ne quad\">{{cite map|url=http://gis.ny.gov/gisdata/quads/drg24/dotpreview/index.cfm?code=q8 |title=Buffalo NE Digital Raster Quadrangle|publisher=New York State Department of Transportation|year=1989|scale=1:24,000|accessdate=January 22, 2010}}</ref> (near [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]) and rests on 11.9 acres (48,000 m\u00b2). There are three buildings on the grounds: the Academic Building, Field House, and Innovation Center. The Brothers Residence was torn down in 2008 and is now the site of The Cullen Center for Excellence in Science, which includes a new residence on the top floor.\n\nWithin St. Joseph\u2019s Collegiate Institute, there are two academic computer labs, a newly updated Computer Graphics Lab in the art wing, and a Music Lab that employs Mac and Windows computers. The library also contains workstations for internet access. The Fine Arts facility includes a fully functioning black-box theatre, band room and sound-proof practice facilities<ref>https://www.sjci.com/apps/pages/fastfacts</ref>.\n\nAthletics are also an integral part of the St. Joe\u2019s experience and students are able to take advantage of both indoor and outdoor facilities. A modern weight room, renovated in 2014, two gymnasiums, a field house, and the 183,961 square foot, all-weather artificial turf Robert T. Scott AFSC Athletic Field Complex comprise the facilities of the athletic department. The Cullen Center for Excellence in science building was finished in fall 2009 and is presently in use. Classes include lab stations, smartboards and a work area for each student.\n\n==Sports==\nSt. Joseph's Collegiate Institute offers an extensive athletic program consisting of 16 sports, with most sports offering multiple levels of competition.  St. Joe's has won the Supremacy Cup, recognizing the top overall athletic program in the [[Monsignor Martin Athletic Association]]'s AA League, 31 times in the 58 years of the league's existence.<ref>http://www.sjci.com/athletics.php</ref>\n\nIn addition to interscholastic competition, St. Joe's offers a number of intramural athletic programs and maintains a vocal group of student supporters at their major sports events.\n\nThe Marauders' main rival is [[Canisius High School]].\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Michael A. Caliguiri]] - noted cancer researcher and President & Physician-in-Chief, [[City of Hope National Medical Center]]\n*[[Craig Cirbus]] \u2013 former [[University at Buffalo]] head football coach\n* [[Jimmy Collins]] \u2013 first player selected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] primarily as a [[third baseman]]<ref>[http://www.gbshof.com/1993/jimmy_collins.html The Greater Buffalo Sports Hall of Fame: Jimmy Collins] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711080822/http://www.gbshof.com/1993/jimmy_collins.html |date=2011-07-11 }}</ref>\n* [[Don Criqui]] \u2013 football commentator for [[CBS Sports]] and the [[University of Notre Dame]] and member of the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]<ref>[http://www.gbshof.com/2003/don_criqui.html The Greater Buffalo Sports Hall of Fame: Don Criqui] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711080857/http://www.gbshof.com/2003/don_criqui.html |date=2011-07-11 }}</ref>\n* [[William Joseph Donovan|William \"Wild Bill\" Joseph Donovan]] \u2013 lawyer, general and founder of the [[Office of Strategic Services]], winner of the Congressional [[Medal of Honor]], \"founder\" of the [[CIA]]<ref>[http://www.samhoyt.com/index.php?src=news&refno=435&category=Press%20Releases Assemblymembers Sam Hoyt and Mark J.F. Schroeder honor the legacy of General William Donovan]</ref>\n* [[Eugene M. Fahey]] \u2013 Judge of the New York Court of Appeals<ref name=\"NYC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nycourts.gov/ctapps/jfahey.htm |title=Honorable Eugene M. Fahey |publisher=Nycourts.gov |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2017-10-05}}</ref>\n* [[Dennis Gilbert (ice hockey)]] \u2013 Professional ice hockey defenseman with the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] of the [[National Hockey League]]<ref>https://www.hockey-reference.com/players/g/gilbede01.html</ref>\n* [[John Patrick Hopkins]] \u2013 mayor of Chicago (1893\u201395)\n* [[Chad Kelly]] \u2013 American football quarterback\n*[[David Leggio]] - Professional ice hockey goaltender and United States Olympian\n* [[Christopher Markus]] \u2013 [[Emmy Award]]-winning screenwriter, best known for [[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]], [[Captain America: The First Avenger]], [[The Life and Death of Peter Sellers]] and [[Avengers: Infinity War]] \n*[[Jaylen Morris]] - Professional basketball player who has played for the [[Atlanta Hawks]] and [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n* [[Vaughn Parker]] \u2013 former [[NFL]] [[tackle (American football position)|tackle]], [[San Diego Chargers]] and [[Washington Redskins]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaughn A. Parker \u201989 Addresses The Class Of 2006|url=http://www.sjci.com/ftp_only/myers/spring_2006vs2.pdf|format=PDF|work=The Collegiate|location=St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute|page=4|date=Spring 2006|access-date=May 18, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106152649/http://www.sjci.com/ftp_only/myers/spring_2006vs2.pdf|archive-date=January 6, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Paxon]] \u2013 [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]], 1989-99<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=p000148 Biographical Directory of the United States Congress: William L. Paxon], bioguide.congress.gov; accessed August 8, 2016.</ref>\n* [[Carmen A. Puliafito]] \u2013 Dean, Keck School of Medicine at the [[University of Southern California]] {{When|date=August 2016}}\n* [[James Edward Quigley]] \u2013 Archbishop of Chicago (1903\u201315)\n* [[Naaman Roosevelt]] \u2013 wide receiver, [[Buffalo Bills]] (2010\u201311) <ref>[http://www.nfl.com/player/naamanroosevelt/2507830/profile Naaman Roosevelt Profile], NFL.com; accessed February 28, 2018.</ref>\n* [[Sean Ryan (football player)|Sean Ryan]] \u2013 tight end, [[National Football League]]<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/player/seanryan/2506010/profile Sean Ryan Profile], NFL.com; accessed February 28, 2018.</ref> (2004\u201309)\n* [[Cole Schneider]] \u2013 hockey player, [[New York Rangers]]<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/player/cole-schneider-8476766 Cole Schneider profile], NHL.com; accessed August 8, 2016.</ref>\n* [[William F. Sheehan]] \u2013 Lawyer, politician; Lieutenant Governor of New York (1892\u201394)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.sjci.com/ St. Joseph's Collegiate Institute]\n\n{{Monsignor Martin Athletic Association}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo}}\n{{Boys' schools in New York State}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Joseph's Collegiate Institute}}\n[[Category:Lasallian schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "WildCowboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni:fix spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Joseph%27s_Collegiate_Institute"}
{"title_page": "WMSD", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station\n | name = WMSD\n | image = \n | city = [[Rose Township, Ogemaw County, Michigan|Rose Township, Michigan]]\n | area = [http://www.radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/pat?call=WMSD&service=FM&status=L&hours=U]\n | branding = Bible Believing Radio\n | slogan = \n | airdate = August 11, 2000\n | frequency = 90.9 [[MHz]]\n | format = [[Fundamentalist Christianity]]\n | power = 5,000 [[watt]]s\n | erp = \n | class = A\n | callsign_meaning = '''W'''e '''M'''agnify '''S'''ound '''D'''octrine\n | former_callsigns = \n | owner = Bible Baptist Church\n | licensee = \n | sister_stations = \n | webcast = \n | website = [http://www.wmsdradio.com]\n | affiliations = \n}}\n\n'''WMSD''' (90.9 FM) is an FM [[radio station]] licensed to [[Rose Township, Ogemaw County, Michigan|Rose Township, Michigan]].  The station proper is located in the town of [[Lupton, Michigan]].\n\nIn July 2000, a construction permit was issued and by August 11, 2000 the station began broadcasting at 90.9 FM.  The station prefers to refer to themselves as a Bible believing radio station rather than a Christian station. {{Fact|date=November 2007}}\n\nThe station was originally an affiliate of the [[Fundamental Broadcasting Network]], located in [[New Bern, North Carolina]]. In March 2005, the station began local programming via its own automation system, allowing the station to control its own programming schedule.\n\nThe station is a ministry of Bible Baptist Church of Lupton, Michigan.\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.michiguide.com/dials/rad-m/wmsd.html Michiguide.com - WMSD History]\n\n==External links==\n*{{FM station data|WMSD}}\n\n{{Religious Radio Stations in Michigan}}\n\n{{coord|44.433|N|84.009|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Ogemaw County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Michigan|MSD]]\n\n\n{{Michigan-radio-station-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station\n | name = WMSD\n | image = \n | city = [[Rose Township, Ogemaw County, Michigan|Rose Township, Michigan]]\n | area = [http://www.radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/pat?call=WMSD&service=FM&status=L&hours=U]\n | branding = Bible Believing Radio\n | slogan = \n | airdate = August 11, 2000\n | frequency = 90.9 [[MHz]]\n | format = [[Fundamentalist Christianity]]\n | power = 5,000 [[watt]]s\n | erp = \n | class = A\n | callsign_meaning = '''W'''e '''M'''agnify '''S'''ound '''D'''octrine\n | former_callsigns = \n | owner = Bible Baptist Church\n | licensee = \n | sister_stations = \n | webcast = \n | website = [http://www.wmsdradio.com]\n | affiliations = \n}}\n\n'''WMSD''' (90.9 FM) is an FM [[radio station]] licensed to [[Rose Township, Ogemaw County, Michigan|Rose Township, Michigan]].  The station proper is located in the town of [[Lupton, Michigan]].\n\nIn July 2000, a construction permit was issued and by August 11, 2000 the station began broadcasting at 90.9 FM.  The station prefers to refer to themselves as a Bible believing radio station rather than a Christian station. {{Fact|date=November 2007}}\n\nThe station was originally an affiliate of the [[Fundamental Broadcasting Network]], located in [[New Bern, North Carolina]]. In March 2005, the station began local programming via its own automation system, allowing the station to control its own programming schedule.\n\nThe station is a ministry of Bible Baptist Church of Lupton, Michigan.\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.michiguide.com/dials/rad-m/wmsd.html Michiguide.com - WMSD History]\n\n==External links==\n*{{FM station data|WMSD}}\n\n{{Religous Radio Stations in Michigan}}\n\n{{coord|44.433|N|84.009|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Ogemaw County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Michigan|MSD]]\n\n\n{{Michigan-radio-station-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cilidus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WMSD"}
{"title_page": "Melissa Doyle", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Melissa Doyle\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM|size=100%}}\n| image        = Melissa Doyle (19919564043).jpg\n| image_size   = 230px\n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|02|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n| nationality  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Charles Sturt University]]\n| occupation   =  [[Journalist]]; television & radio presenter, author\n| years active = 1990\u2013present \n| employer     = \n| children     = 2\n| website      = [https://7news.com.au/sunday-night/the-team Sunday Night profile]\n| spouse       = \n| credits      =  {{unbulleted list|[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|''Sunrise'']] co-host {{small|(2002\u20132013)}}|{{nowrap|''[[Seven News]] Sydney'' {{small|(2015\u20132016)}} }}|''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' {{small|(2015\u20132019)}} }}\n}}\n\n'''Melissa Jane Doyle''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 10 February 1970) is an Australian television presenter, author and journalist. Doyle currently hosts ''Weekend Breakfast'' on ''[[Smooth (radio network)|smoothfm]]'' and is a Senior Reporter and presenter for ''[[Seven News]]''. She was previously co-host of the [[Seven Network]]'s breakfast television program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' from 2002 to 2013 alongside [[David Koch (television presenter)|David Koch]] <ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-au/entertainment/tv/newsreader-chris-bath-to-leave-channel-seven-melissa-doyle-announced-as-replacement/ar-BBlbT66.html|title=Newsreader Chris Bath to leave Channel Seven, Melissa Doyle  announced as replacement|date=17 June 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and host of ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' from 2015 to 2019. ''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Team|url=https://7news.com.au/sunday-night/the-team|accessdate=15 May 2019|date=15 May 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nDoyle attended the [[Pymble Ladies' College]]. She studied communications at [[Charles Sturt University]] and during her studies she was a broadcaster with on-campus community radio station [[2MCE]]-FM. She gained a cadetship at [[WIN Television]]'s [[Canberra]] bureau in 1990, later becoming their weather presenter. Doyle then moved to [[Prime Television]] in 1993, where she was a news anchor and general reporter.\n\nAfter her stint at Prime ended in 1995, Doyle joined the Seven Network as a Canberra-based political reporter before moving to Sydney where she read the news on ''11AM'', reported the news and read the afternoon updates. Doyle was one of ''Sunrise's'' original hosts before it was axed in 1999, before being resurrected in 2000, and which she rejoined in 2002. In 1999 she was the fill in presenter of the last bulletin of 11AM due to the incumbent presenter [[Anne Fulwood]] having already relocated to Melbourne.<ref>{{Citation|last=TelevisionAU|title=HSV7 Eleven AM final edition 1999|date=2014-05-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kU14ER2bzxI|accessdate=2016-07-19}}</ref>  She also had a stint reading the ''[[Seven News|Seven Late News]]''.\n\nIn 2000, she took over as host of Sydney's ''[[Today Tonight]]'' following the departure of [[Stan Grant (journalist)|Stan Grant]]. She stayed until March 2001 when she went on maternity leave.\n\nDoyle supports the [[Greater Western Sydney Giants]] [[Australian Football League|AFL]] team;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beveridge|first1=Riley|title=Your AFL club's most famous supporters, from Barack Obama to Cam Newton|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/your-afl-clubs-most-famous-supporters-from-barack-obama-to-cam-newton/news-story/03eb54659866d587cf9c2cc4b9f3d8c5|website=Fox Sports|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  in 2012, she was named as the GWS Giants' inaugural No. 1 Ticket Holder.\n\n===''Sunrise''===\n\nDoyle returned to Seven from maternity leave in a variety of news and presenting roles before being asked to front a revamped ''Sunrise'' program with [[Chris Reason]], who was latter replaced by David Koch. Together, Doyle and Koch under the guidance of Executive producer Adam Boland, surpassed their incumbent opposition and market leaders, ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' on the [[Nine Network]]. They built the program from a virtually zero viewer base to be the leading breakfast television program in Australia and there it remained throughout Doyle's tenure on the program. She was then dubbed the 'Queen of Australian Brekky TV'.\n\nIn 2003, Doyle enjoyed a very public pregnancy with her second child, who was born in December of that year.\n\nDoyle was nominated for the Silver Logie as Most Popular Television Presenter in 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009 and 2010. She was the only female nominated in that category.\n\nDoyle was involved in legal proceedings in which it was alleged she identified a minor who was divorcing his parents. The divorce case was being heard in the Victorian Children's Court and because the boy was only 14 years old he couldn't be named. But ''Sunrise'', as well as a number of other news outlets, including the ''[[Herald Sun|Sunday Herald Sun]]'' and ''Today Tonight'', allegedly identified him and the journalists/presenters were charged with contempt of court. The journalists and presenters/hosts were all acquitted but the Seven Network, its news director, ''Today Tonight''{{'}}s executive producer and the ''Sunday Herald Sun'' and its editor-in-chief were convicted.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nWhile at the helm of Sunrise she was at the front line of many of Australia's biggest stories of the era including, but not limited to, [[Beaconsfield Mine collapse]] and the [[2010\u201311 Queensland floods]], and international stories such as the Royal Wedding.\n\nOn 20 June 2013, Doyle announced that she would be stepping down as ''Sunrise'' co-host to take on a national role within the Seven Network. She presented her final show on 9 August of the same year. Her farewell program was the highest rating edition of the show that year.\n\n===After ''Sunrise''===\nIt was revealed in August 2013 that Doyle would present a new national bulletin of [[Seven News|''Seven Afternoon News'']] at 4pm on weekdays with former ''Today Tonight'' host [[Matthew White (journalist)|Matt White]], as well as a new national bulletin ''[[Seven News|Seven News at 7]] ''on Seven's digital channel [[7Two]]. This bulletin was discontinued in May 2014.\n\nDoyle began presenting ''Seven News at 7 ''on 12 August and ''Seven Afternoon News'' on 19 August. Doyle also hosted the first debate of the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 Federal Election]] between Labor leader and then Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] and Liberal leader [[Tony Abbott]], on 7Two on 11 August.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130811210818/http://au.tv.yahoo.com/sunrise/soapbox/article/-/18421972/melissa-doyle-sunrise-last-day-final-show-photos-video Melissa Doyle's last day on Sunrise]. tv.yahoo.com</ref> She was also a part of the 2013 federal election broadcast with [[Chris Bath]], Mark Riley and Matt White.\n\nIn October 2013, Doyle joined [[Smooth (radio network)|smoothfm]] to host ''Weekend Breakfast'' from 6am to 10am. The program has continued to grow in popularity with her show recording the highest ever market share percentage in the June 2014 Rating Survey and making the program the #2 FM weekend breakfast program for All People 10+. In the coveted Females 40\u201354 ratings segment, Doyle's program was the #1 FM Weekend Breakfast program, recording its highest ever share result in the June ratings survey and the only FM station with over 20% share.\n\nIn December 2013, Doyle co-hosted [[Carols in the Domain]] with [[Matthew White (journalist)|Matt White]].\n\nIn October 2014, Doyle won Best Newcomer On-Air (Metro) at the Australian Commercial Radio Awards.<ref>[http://mumbrella.com.au/jonesy-and-amanda-big-winners-at-radio-awards-257411 Jonesy and Amanda the big winners at radio awards]. Mumbrella (19 October 2014). Retrieved on 2015-12-06.</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that Doyle would replace Chris Bath on ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' and ''[[Seven News|Seven News Sydney]]'' due to Bath's resignation from the Seven Network.<ref name=\"smh\"/> Doyle signed off from ''Seven Afternoon News'' for the last time in late July.\n\nIn August 2016, it was announced that Doyle would move into a new expanding role as host and senior correspondent on ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]].'' As a result of Melissa's new position [[Michael Usher]] replaced her on [[Seven News|''Seven News Sydney'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/melissa-doyle-takes-expanding-role-sunday-night-388000|title=Melissa Doyle takes on expanding role with Sunday Night - Mumbrella|date=2016-08-15|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Doyle won Best Music Presenter at the Australian Commercial Radio Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://startsat60.com/lifestyle/style/melissa-doyle-sparkles-in-figure-hugging-gown|title=Melissa Doyle sparkles in figure-hugging gown|date=2018-10-21|work=Starts at 60|access-date=2018-10-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\n\nIn October 2007, Doyle's first book, ''The Working Mothers Survival Guide'' (co-written with Jo Scard), was published by Allen & Unwin. It sold over 10,000 copies in its first print run. In 2014, she released her second book, ''Alphabet Soup''. The memoir was the biggest selling Australian memoir in the market during its first few months on bookshelves. Doyle and Koch also co-hosted another [[Seven Network]] production ''[[Where Are They Now? (Australian TV program)|Where Are They Now?]]''.\n\nIn 2008, Doyle was selected to front a new documentary program on the Seven Network called ''[[The Zoo (Australian TV series)|The Zoo]]''. The show had a six-week run during the first half of 2008. A second series of ''[[The Zoo (Australian TV series)|The Zoo]]'' commenced on air in October 2008. It generated an audience of over 1.7 million people in each of its first three weeks making it one of the Top Five Programs on Australian television for that week, and one of the highest ranking programs of the year.\n\nDoyle previously wrote a weekly column in Australia's highest selling newspaper, the ''Sunday Herald Sun'' in Melbourne called \"Balancing Act\". The column talked about her experiences as a working mother.\n\n==Charity and honours==\nDoyle is the National Patron for Make A Wish and an ambassador for [[The Alannah and Madeline Foundation]], [[Westmead Children's Hospital]], [[World Vision Australia|World Vision]], Children's Cancer Institute and the National Breast Cancer Foundation. Melissa is also an ambassador for the Federal Government's National Road Safety Council and is the Number One Ticket Holder for the [[Greater Western Sydney Giants|GWS Giants]] (AFL) and Whittlesea Eagles (Vic AFL). She was also the Chairperson for the GIANTS Foundation Charity, established in 2013 and served in this role until 2018, when she was appointed to the Board of Directors of the GIANTS in 2018.\n\nDoyle was appointed a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] in 2016 for significant service to the community through representational roles with a range of charitable groups, and to the broadcast media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2016/dvvsf4sc1d05nwgt/Media%20Notes%20-%20AM%20%28A-L%29%281%29.pdf |title=Member (AM) in the General Division of the Order of Australia (A-L) |work=Australia Day 2016 Honours Lists |publisher=[[Governor-General of Australia|Office of the Governor-General of Australia]] |date=25 January 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.melissadoyle.com.au Melissa Doyle's official site]\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20120211151504/http://www.workingmotherssurvivalguide.com/, Website for Melissa Doyle's book\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080210164445/http://health.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=6377 Melissa Doyle], [[Ninemsn]] ''Health'', June 2004 issue of GoodMedicine magazine\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107052900/http://www.who.com/who/magazine/article/0%2C19636%2C7401061204-1562669%2C00.html Interview on WHO.com with Mel and Kochie about their Cool the Globe campaign]\n*{{IMDb name|1745612}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]] <br />Host & Senior Correspondent\n| years = August 2015 \u2013 November 2019\n| before = [[Chris Bath]]\n| after = Program axed\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = ''[[Seven News#Sydney|Seven News Sydney]]'' <br /> Friday & Saturday presenter\n| years = August 2015 \u2013 August 2016\n| before = [[Chris Bath]]\n| after = [[Michael Usher]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Seven News|''Seven Afternoon News'']] <br />Presenter<br />with [[Matthew White (journalist)|Matt White]] (2013-2014)<br /> & Solo (2014-2015)\n| years = August 2013 \u2013 July 2015\n| before = [[Rebecca Maddern]]\n| after = [[Ann Sanders]]<br /><small>Each state later gained their own edition</small>\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Mark Ferguson (television presenter)|Mark Ferguson]]\n| as = Fill-in presenter\n}} \n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Seven News|''Seven News at 7'']] <br />Presenter\n| years = August 2013 \u2013 April 2014\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Program axed\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|''Sunrise'']] <br />Co-host with [[David Koch (television presenter)|David Koch]]\n| years = 2002\u20132013\n| before = [[Georgie Gardner]]\n| after = [[Samantha Armytage]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Stan Grant (journalist)|Stan Grant]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = ''[[Today Tonight]]'' <br />New South Wales presenter\n| years = 2000\u20132001\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Naomi Robson]] <br /><small>NSW edition merged with Victorian edition</small>\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SevenNewsAnchors}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doyle, Melissa}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Australian television journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Seven News presenters]]\n[[Category:Charles Sturt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pymble Ladies' College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Melissa Doyle\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM|size=100%}}\n| image        = Melissa Doyle (19919564043).jpg\n| image_size   = 230px\n| caption      = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|02|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n| nationality  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Charles Sturt University]]\n| occupation   =  [[Journalist]]; television & radio presenter, author\n| years active = 1990\u2013present \n| employer     = \n| children     = 2\n| website      = [https://7news.com.au/sunday-night/the-team Sunday Night profile]\n| spouse       = \n| credits      =  {{unbulleted list|[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|''Sunrise'']] co-host {{small|(2002\u20132013)}}|{{nowrap|''[[Seven News]] Sydney'' {{small|(2015\u20132016)}} }}|''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' {{small|(2015\u20132019)|'' The Latest:  [[Seven News]]''{{small|2020-present}} }} }}\n}}\n\n'''Melissa Jane Doyle''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 10 February 1970) is an Australian television presenter, author and journalist. Doyle currently hosts ''Weekend Breakfast'' on ''[[Smooth (radio network)|smoothfm]]'' and is a Senior Reporter and presenter for ''[[Seven News]]''. She was previously co-host of the [[Seven Network]]'s breakfast television program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' from 2002 to 2013 alongside [[David Koch (television presenter)|David Koch]] <ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.msn.com/en-au/entertainment/tv/newsreader-chris-bath-to-leave-channel-seven-melissa-doyle-announced-as-replacement/ar-BBlbT66.html|title=Newsreader Chris Bath to leave Channel Seven, Melissa Doyle  announced as replacement|date=17 June 2015}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and host of ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' from 2015 to 2019. ''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Team|url=https://7news.com.au/sunday-night/the-team|accessdate=15 May 2019|date=15 May 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nDoyle attended the [[Pymble Ladies' College]]. She studied communications at [[Charles Sturt University]] and during her studies she was a broadcaster with on-campus community radio station [[2MCE]]-FM. She gained a cadetship at [[WIN Television]]'s [[Canberra]] bureau in 1990, later becoming their weather presenter. Doyle then moved to [[Prime Television]] in 1993, where she was a news anchor and general reporter.\n\nAfter her stint at Prime ended in 1995, Doyle joined the Seven Network as a Canberra-based political reporter before moving to Sydney where she read the news on ''11AM'', reported the news and read the afternoon updates. Doyle was one of ''Sunrise's'' original hosts before it was axed in 1999, before being resurrected in 2000, and which she rejoined in 2002. In 1999 she was the fill in presenter of the last bulletin of 11AM due to the incumbent presenter [[Anne Fulwood]] having already relocated to Melbourne.<ref>{{Citation|last=TelevisionAU|title=HSV7 Eleven AM final edition 1999|date=2014-05-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kU14ER2bzxI|accessdate=2016-07-19}}</ref>  She also had a stint reading the ''[[Seven News|Seven Late News]]''.\n\nIn 2000, she took over as host of Sydney's ''[[Today Tonight]]'' following the departure of [[Stan Grant (journalist)|Stan Grant]]. She stayed until March 2001 when she went on maternity leave.\n\nDoyle supports the [[Greater Western Sydney Giants]] [[Australian Football League|AFL]] team;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beveridge|first1=Riley|title=Your AFL club's most famous supporters, from Barack Obama to Cam Newton|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/your-afl-clubs-most-famous-supporters-from-barack-obama-to-cam-newton/news-story/03eb54659866d587cf9c2cc4b9f3d8c5|website=Fox Sports|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  in 2012, she was named as the GWS Giants' inaugural No. 1 Ticket Holder. \n\nafter [[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]] Axed In 2019 Melissa Return The Latest [[Seven News]] join the team and [[Michael Usher]]\n\n===''Sunrise''===\n\nDoyle returned to Seven from maternity leave in a variety of news and presenting roles before being asked to front a revamped ''Sunrise'' program with [[Chris Reason]], who was latter replaced by David Koch. Together, Doyle and Koch under the guidance of Executive producer Adam Boland, surpassed their incumbent opposition and market leaders, ''[[Today (Australian TV program)|Today]]'' on the [[Nine Network]]. They built the program from a virtually zero viewer base to be the leading breakfast television program in Australia and there it remained throughout Doyle's tenure on the program. She was then dubbed the 'Queen of Australian Brekky TV'.\n\nIn 2003, Doyle enjoyed a very public pregnancy with her second child, who was born in December of that year.\n\nDoyle was nominated for the Silver Logie as Most Popular Television Presenter in 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009 and 2010. She was the only female nominated in that category.\n\nDoyle was involved in legal proceedings in which it was alleged she identified a minor who was divorcing his parents. The divorce case was being heard in the Victorian Children's Court and because the boy was only 14 years old he couldn't be named. But ''Sunrise'', as well as a number of other news outlets, including the ''[[Herald Sun|Sunday Herald Sun]]'' and ''Today Tonight'', allegedly identified him and the journalists/presenters were charged with contempt of court. The journalists and presenters/hosts were all acquitted but the Seven Network, its news director, ''Today Tonight''{{'}}s executive producer and the ''Sunday Herald Sun'' and its editor-in-chief were convicted.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nWhile at the helm of Sunrise she was at the front line of many of Australia's biggest stories of the era including, but not limited to, [[Beaconsfield Mine collapse]] and the [[2010\u201311 Queensland floods]], and international stories such as the Royal Wedding.\n\nOn 20 June 2013, Doyle announced that she would be stepping down as ''Sunrise'' co-host to take on a national role within the Seven Network. She presented her final show on 9 August of the same year. Her farewell program was the highest rating edition of the show that year.\n\n===After ''Sunrise''===\nIt was revealed in August 2013 that Doyle would present a new national bulletin of [[Seven News|''Seven Afternoon News'']] at 4pm on weekdays with former ''Today Tonight'' host [[Matthew White (journalist)|Matt White]], as well as a new national bulletin ''[[Seven News|Seven News at 7]] ''on Seven's digital channel [[7Two]]. This bulletin was discontinued in May 2014.\n\nDoyle began presenting ''Seven News at 7 ''on 12 August and ''Seven Afternoon News'' on 19 August. Doyle also hosted the first debate of the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 Federal Election]] between Labor leader and then Prime Minister [[Kevin Rudd]] and Liberal leader [[Tony Abbott]], on 7Two on 11 August.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130811210818/http://au.tv.yahoo.com/sunrise/soapbox/article/-/18421972/melissa-doyle-sunrise-last-day-final-show-photos-video Melissa Doyle's last day on Sunrise]. tv.yahoo.com</ref> She was also a part of the 2013 federal election broadcast with [[Chris Bath]], Mark Riley and Matt White.\n\nIn October 2013, Doyle joined [[Smooth (radio network)|smoothfm]] to host ''Weekend Breakfast'' from 6am to 10am. The program has continued to grow in popularity with her show recording the highest ever market share percentage in the June 2014 Rating Survey and making the program the #2 FM weekend breakfast program for All People 10+. In the coveted Females 40\u201354 ratings segment, Doyle's program was the #1 FM Weekend Breakfast program, recording its highest ever share result in the June ratings survey and the only FM station with over 20% share.\n\nIn December 2013, Doyle co-hosted [[Carols in the Domain]] with [[Matthew White (journalist)|Matt White]].\n\nIn October 2014, Doyle won Best Newcomer On-Air (Metro) at the Australian Commercial Radio Awards.<ref>[http://mumbrella.com.au/jonesy-and-amanda-big-winners-at-radio-awards-257411 Jonesy and Amanda the big winners at radio awards]. Mumbrella (19 October 2014). Retrieved on 2015-12-06.</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that Doyle would replace Chris Bath on ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]]'' and ''[[Seven News|Seven News Sydney]]'' due to Bath's resignation from the Seven Network.<ref name=\"smh\"/> Doyle signed off from ''Seven Afternoon News'' for the last time in late July.\n\nIn August 2016, it was announced that Doyle would move into a new expanding role as host and senior correspondent on ''[[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]].'' As a result of Melissa's new position [[Michael Usher]] replaced her on [[Seven News|''Seven News Sydney'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/melissa-doyle-takes-expanding-role-sunday-night-388000|title=Melissa Doyle takes on expanding role with Sunday Night - Mumbrella|date=2016-08-15|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Doyle won Best Music Presenter at the Australian Commercial Radio Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://startsat60.com/lifestyle/style/melissa-doyle-sparkles-in-figure-hugging-gown|title=Melissa Doyle sparkles in figure-hugging gown|date=2018-10-21|work=Starts at 60|access-date=2018-10-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\n\nIn October 2007, Doyle's first book, ''The Working Mothers Survival Guide'' (co-written with Jo Scard), was published by Allen & Unwin. It sold over 10,000 copies in its first print run. In 2014, she released her second book, ''Alphabet Soup''. The memoir was the biggest selling Australian memoir in the market during its first few months on bookshelves. Doyle and Koch also co-hosted another [[Seven Network]] production ''[[Where Are They Now? (Australian TV program)|Where Are They Now?]]''.\n\nIn 2008, Doyle was selected to front a new documentary program on the Seven Network called ''[[The Zoo (Australian TV series)|The Zoo]]''. The show had a six-week run during the first half of 2008. A second series of ''[[The Zoo (Australian TV series)|The Zoo]]'' commenced on air in October 2008. It generated an audience of over 1.7 million people in each of its first three weeks making it one of the Top Five Programs on Australian television for that week, and one of the highest ranking programs of the year.\n\nDoyle previously wrote a weekly column in Australia's highest selling newspaper, the ''Sunday Herald Sun'' in Melbourne called \"Balancing Act\". The column talked about her experiences as a working mother.\n\n==Charity and honours==\nDoyle is the National Patron for Make A Wish and an ambassador for [[The Alannah and Madeline Foundation]], [[Westmead Children's Hospital]], [[World Vision Australia|World Vision]], Children's Cancer Institute and the National Breast Cancer Foundation. Melissa is also an ambassador for the Federal Government's National Road Safety Council and is the Number One Ticket Holder for the [[Greater Western Sydney Giants|GWS Giants]] (AFL) and Whittlesea Eagles (Vic AFL). She was also the Chairperson for the GIANTS Foundation Charity, established in 2013 and served in this role until 2018, when she was appointed to the Board of Directors of the GIANTS in 2018.\n\nDoyle was appointed a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] in 2016 for significant service to the community through representational roles with a range of charitable groups, and to the broadcast media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2016/dvvsf4sc1d05nwgt/Media%20Notes%20-%20AM%20%28A-L%29%281%29.pdf |title=Member (AM) in the General Division of the Order of Australia (A-L) |work=Australia Day 2016 Honours Lists |publisher=[[Governor-General of Australia|Office of the Governor-General of Australia]] |date=25 January 2016 |accessdate=8 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204212005/https://www.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2016/dvvsf4sc1d05nwgt/Media%20Notes%20-%20AM%20%28A-L%29%281%29.pdf |archive-date=4 February 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.melissadoyle.com.au Melissa Doyle's official site]\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20120211151504/http://www.workingmotherssurvivalguide.com/, Website for Melissa Doyle's book\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080210164445/http://health.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=6377 Melissa Doyle], [[Ninemsn]] ''Health'', June 2004 issue of GoodMedicine magazine\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070107052900/http://www.who.com/who/magazine/article/0%2C19636%2C7401061204-1562669%2C00.html Interview on WHO.com with Mel and Kochie about their Cool the Globe campaign]\n*{{IMDb name|1745612}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| title = The Latest: [[Seven News]] <br  />Presenter\n| years  = 2020-Present\n| before = Program Started\n| after  = Incumbent\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Sunday Night (Australian TV program)|Sunday Night]] <br />Host & Senior Corresponden